export const GRAMMAR_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"gi01",title:"Present Perfect vs Past Simple",q:"The government ___ three new universities since 2015.",opts:["built","has built","had built","builds"],ans:1,exp:"Present perfect links a past action to the present moment. 'Since 2015' is a signal that the action started in the past and is still relevant now — the universities still exist. Past simple would say 'The government built three universities in 2015' (completed, specific time, no connection to now). Present perfect focuses on the result in the present rather than on when the action happened.",tip:"Present perfect signals: since, already, yet, just, ever, never, recently, so far, up to now, for (+ duration). In academic writing: 'Research has shown that...', 'Scholars have argued...', 'This study has demonstrated...'. Use past simple for completed past actions with a specific time: 'Smith (2019) argued...', 'The policy was introduced in 2010.'"},
  {id:"gi02",title:"Passive Voice — Present",q:"English ___ widely in international business meetings.",opts:["speaks","is spoken","has spoken","was speaking"],ans:1,exp:"Passive voice reverses the typical active structure. In the active, the agent (people) performs the action on the object (English). In the passive, the object becomes the grammatical subject (English) and receives the action. The passive is formed with: subject + to be (conjugated) + past participle. The agent ('by people') is often omitted when unknown or unimportant.",tip:"When to use passive in academic writing: when the agent is unknown ('Participants were recruited'), when the agent is unimportant ('Data were collected over six months'), or when you want to maintain formal, impersonal tone ('It was found that...'). When NOT to use passive: when the agent is known and important for the argument, as active voice is clearer and more direct: 'Smith (2019) found that...' rather than 'It was found by Smith (2019) that...'"},
  {id:"gi03",title:"Reported Speech",q:"The professor said: 'Students must submit essays on Friday.' → He said that students ___ essays on Friday.",opts:["must submit","had to submit","should to submit","will submit"],ans:1,exp:"Reported speech requires 'backshifting' — moving the original tense one step into the past. 'Must' does not have a past tense in English, so it becomes 'had to' in reported speech. Other backshifts: will→would, can→could, may→might, am/is/are→was/were, have/has→had. The original words are not used verbatim — only the meaning is reported, adjusted for time and person.",tip:"Reporting verb backshifts: must→had to, will→would, can→could, may→might, is/are→was/were, have→had. Time expressions also shift: now→then, today→that day, tomorrow→the following day, yesterday→the day before. Academic reporting verbs: argue, claim, suggest, propose, state, contend, assert, maintain. Example: 'The researchers claimed that the results were significant.'"},
  {id:"gi04",title:"Relative Clauses — Which/Who",q:"The report, ___ was published last week, contains important data.",opts:["that","which","who","whose"],ans:1,exp:"Relative clauses come in two types. DEFINING clauses identify which specific person or thing: 'The student who submitted first received full marks' — without this clause, we don't know which student. DEFINING clauses use 'that' or 'who/which' and have no commas. NON-DEFINING clauses add extra information about something already identified: 'The report, which was published last week, contains important data.' These use 'which/who' and are set off by commas.",tip:"DEFINING relative clauses: no commas, can use 'that' for things. 'The study that examined 500 participants...' NON-DEFINING relative clauses: always use commas, always 'which' (not 'that') for things, 'who' for people. 'The African Union, which was founded in 2002, now has 55 member states.' Academic tip: non-defining clauses add scholarly precision and nuance to arguments."},
  {id:"gi05",title:"Conditionals — Second",q:"If the government ___ more in education, unemployment would decrease significantly.",opts:["invests","invested","had invested","will invest"],ans:1,exp:"The second conditional expresses a hypothetical, unreal, or unlikely situation in the present or future. 'If the government invested' implies it currently does not invest enough — this is a hypothetical condition. The structure is: if + past simple (condition) + would + base verb (result). This is different from the first conditional ('If the government invests, unemployment will decrease'), which expresses a real possibility.",tip:"Second conditional: If + PAST SIMPLE → WOULD + base verb. Used for: hypothetical present/future ('If I had more time, I would research this more'), unlikely situations ('If every country agreed, climate change would be solved'), and polite requests ('Would you mind if I sat here?'). Academic: 'If African governments invested 6% of GDP in education, literacy rates would increase significantly.'"},
  {id:"gi06",title:"Modal Verbs — Deduction",q:"She ___ be exhausted — she has been studying for twelve hours.",opts:["can","could","must","should"],ans:2,exp:"'Must' for deduction expresses certainty about something based on logical reasoning — not a rule or obligation. 'She must be exhausted' means: given the evidence (12 hours of studying), I am certain she is exhausted. Other deduction modals: 'can't be' = I'm certain it's NOT true ('She can't be tired — she only studied for 20 minutes'). 'Might/could be' = possibility, not certainty ('She might be tired').",tip:"Modal deduction scale: MUST = I'm almost certain it's true. SHOULD = I expect it's true (based on normal expectation). MIGHT/COULD = it's possible. CAN'T/COULDN'T = I'm almost certain it's NOT true. Academic: 'This finding must be interpreted with caution.' 'These results could be explained by selection bias.' 'The discrepancy cannot be explained by measurement error alone.'"},
  {id:"gi07",title:"Gerunds and Infinitives",q:"The university encourages students ___ critical thinking skills throughout their degree.",opts:["develop","to develop","developing","developed"],ans:1,exp:"'Encourage' belongs to a category of verbs that require object + infinitive. The structure is: encourage someone TO DO something. You cannot say 'encourages students develop' (no 'to') or 'encourages students developing' (wrong form). Other verbs with this pattern: want someone to do, ask someone to do, advise someone to do, allow someone to do, expect someone to do, persuade someone to do.",tip:"Verbs + OBJECT + INFINITIVE: encourage, want, ask, advise, tell, allow, expect, persuade, require, enable, help, force, permit. Example: 'The programme enables students to develop...' 'Researchers asked participants to complete...' 'The policy requires companies to report...' Contrast with verbs + gerund (no object): avoid, enjoy, finish, recommend. And verbs + object + base verb (no 'to'): make, let, have, help (informal)."},
  {id:"gi08",title:"Articles — Advanced",q:"___ research published in ___ Journal of Education suggests that ___ learning is changing.",opts:["The / the / —","A / a / —","The / a / the","— / The / —"],ans:3,exp:"Articles in English follow complex rules for academic contexts. 'Research' is uncountable in general use — no article needed when referring to research in general. 'Journal of Education' is a unique, specific title — we use 'the' before specific titles. 'Learning' as a general concept needs no article. The key distinction: no article for general/uncountable things; 'the' for specific things that are uniquely identifiable.",tip:"No article (zero article): uncountable nouns in general (research, knowledge, information), plural countable nouns in general (universities, students, researchers), abstract concepts (democracy, education, poverty). THE for: specific things (the government, the results from this study, the theory proposed), superlatives (the most significant finding), unique things (the African Union, the universe). A/AN for: first mention of a countable noun ('A study was conducted'), general membership ('She is a researcher')."},
  {id:"gi09",title:"Conjunctions — Contrast",q:"___ poverty rates have fallen, inequality has actually increased in many regions.",opts:["Although","Despite","However","Because"],ans:0,exp:"'Although' is a subordinating conjunction that introduces a subordinate clause showing contrast or concession. It must be followed by a complete clause with a subject and verb. 'Despite' is a preposition and must be followed by a noun phrase or gerund: 'Despite the decline' or 'Despite declining'. 'However' is a conjunctive adverb that begins a new independent clause, preceded by a full stop or semicolon.",tip:"Contrast connectors — knowing which to use: ALTHOUGH/EVEN THOUGH + clause: 'Although poverty rates have fallen...' DESPITE/IN SPITE OF + noun/gerund: 'Despite the fall in poverty rates...' HOWEVER + new clause (with comma): 'Poverty rates have fallen. However, inequality has increased.' WHEREAS + clause (same sentence): 'Poverty rates have fallen, whereas inequality has increased.' Academic writing uses all four — vary them for precision and style."},
  {id:"gi10",title:"Passive Voice — Past",q:"The colonial borders ___ without considering African ethnic and cultural boundaries.",opts:["drew","were drawn","had drawn","have been drawn"],ans:1,exp:"The past passive uses 'were drawn' because 'borders' (plural) receives the action — someone (the colonial powers) drew the borders, but the sentence focuses on what happened to the borders, not on who did it. The agent (colonial powers) is omitted here because the focus is on the result. Past passive is especially common in academic writing about historical events, scientific experiments, and research procedures.",tip:"Past passive uses: 'was/were + past participle.' Singular subject: 'The policy was introduced in 1990.' Plural subject: 'The participants were randomly assigned.' Common in research writing: 'Data were collected between June and August.' 'The interviews were recorded and transcribed.' 'The analysis was conducted using SPSS.' Passive is preferred over active when the agent is unknown, unimportant, or deliberately de-emphasised for objectivity."},
  {id:"gi11",title:"Cleft Sentences",q:"___ was the lack of funding that caused the project to fail.",opts:["It","This","There","What"],ans:0,exp:"Cleft sentences divide a statement into two parts using 'It was X that...' to place strong emphasis on X. 'It was the lack of funding that caused the failure' emphasises 'lack of funding' as the specific cause. The same idea without emphasis: 'The lack of funding caused the failure.' Cleft sentences are very useful in academic writing when you want to isolate and emphasise a specific element of your argument or analysis.",tip:"Cleft sentence patterns: IT + WAS + focused element + THAT/WHO + rest. 'It was the 2008 financial crisis that triggered the policy change.' 'It was Achebe who first challenged the Western narrative of Africa.' WHAT-clefts: 'What is needed is greater investment in education.' 'What the data reveal is a complex, multi-causal relationship.' These structures add rhetorical force and analytical precision."},
  {id:"gi12",title:"Future Perfect",q:"By the time she graduates, she ___ over 50 academic essays.",opts:["will write","will have written","writes","is going to write"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect is used when you need to describe an action that will be completed BEFORE a specific future point in time. 'By the time she graduates' is the future reference point; 'will have written' will be completed before that point. The structure is: will have + past participle. This tense is less common but essential for expressing timing relationships in academic planning, projections, and logical sequences.",tip:"Future perfect signals: by the time, by + future date, before, when (future). 'By 2030, the global population will have reached 8.5 billion.' 'Before the study ends, researchers will have collected over 1,000 responses.' 'By the time you read this, the policy will have changed.' In academic writing, future perfect is used for projections, timelines, and anticipated outcomes in research plans and policy analysis."},
  {id:"gi13",title:"Inversion for Emphasis",q:"___ had the researchers published their findings when criticism began.",opts:["Hardly","Scarcely","No sooner","Barely"],ans:2,exp:"'No sooner...than' is an idiomatic inversion structure used to express that one event happened immediately after another. Standard: 'The researchers had barely published their findings when criticism began.' With inversion: 'No sooner had the researchers published their findings than criticism began.' These structures begin with a negative element (Hardly, Scarcely, No sooner) and require inverted word order (auxiliary verb before subject).",tip:"Negative inversion structures: NO SOONER...THAN ('No sooner had she arrived than he left'), HARDLY/SCARCELY/BARELY...WHEN ('Hardly had the policy been announced when protests began'). These all require: negative adverb + auxiliary + subject + past participle. They are formal, literary, and rhetorical — found in sophisticated academic and editorial writing. Using them correctly signals advanced English proficiency."},
  {id:"gi14",title:"Quantifiers — Advanced",q:"___ the students who participated in the study showed significant improvement.",opts:["Most of","The most of","Most","Almost"],ans:0,exp:"'Most of the' refers to a specific, identified group that has already been mentioned or is understood from context. 'Most' alone refers to a general, unspecified group. 'Most students struggle with...' (students in general). 'Most of the students in the study showed improvement' (the specific students who participated in this study). 'The most of' does not exist in English — never use this form.",tip:"Quantifier precision: MOST + noun (general): 'Most researchers agree...' MOST OF + the/these/those/possessive + noun (specific): 'Most of the participants reported...', 'Most of Smith's findings...'. ALMOST + ALL: 'Almost all students...' THE MAJORITY OF: 'The majority of the data suggests...' Academic writing requires precise quantification — vague terms like 'many' and 'some' are acceptable, but specifying 'most', 'most of the', or 'the majority' is more precise."},
  {id:"gi15",title:"Participle Clauses",q:"___ in Abidjan, the company has expanded its operations across West Africa.",opts:["Basing","Based","Having based","To base"],ans:1,exp:"Participial phrases with past participles (-ed form) express a passive or completed state that gives context for the main clause. 'Based in Abidjan' = because/since it is based in Abidjan. The implied subject of 'Based in Abidjan' is the same as the main clause subject: the company. Using 'Basing' (active -ing) would imply the company actively bases itself — less natural. 'Having based' would imply it previously based itself, which changes the meaning.",tip:"Past participle clauses: BASED on, BUILT on, FOUNDED on, LOCATED in, SITUATED near, PUBLISHED in. These are extremely common in academic writing: 'Based on these findings, we conclude that...' 'Located in West Africa, Côte d'Ivoire has...' 'Founded in 1999, the organisation has grown to...' Active participle (-ing) for simultaneous actions: 'Examining the data, the researchers noticed a pattern.' Having + past participle for prior completed action: 'Having reviewed the literature, the researchers designed the study.'"},
  {id:"gi16",title:"Conditionals — Third",q:"If the government ___ earlier, the environmental damage could have been avoided.",opts:["acts","acted","had acted","would act"],ans:2,exp:"The third conditional describes a hypothetical past situation that did not happen and its hypothetical result. 'If the government had acted earlier' = but it didn't act early enough. 'The damage could have been avoided' = but it wasn't avoided. This structure expresses regret, criticism, or reflection on past missed opportunities. It cannot be used for present or future situations.",tip:"Third conditional structure: IF + HAD + past participle → WOULD/COULD/MIGHT + HAVE + past participle. 'If researchers had controlled for selection bias, the results would have been more reliable.' 'If African nations had been represented at Bretton Woods, the global financial architecture might have been different.' Academic: use third conditional to analyse counterfactuals — what would have happened under different historical circumstances."},
  {id:"gi17",title:"Nominalisation",q:"The ___ of new policies has led to significant improvements in literacy rates.",opts:["implementing","implementation","implemented","to implement"],ans:1,exp:"Nominalisation converts a verb or adjective into a noun. 'Implement' (verb) → 'implementation' (noun). Academic writing strongly prefers nominal forms because they create distance, formality, and precision. Compare: 'The government implemented new policies. This led to improvements.' (verbal, informal) vs 'The implementation of new policies led to significant improvements.' (nominal, academic). Nominalisations compress information and create more sophisticated sentence structures.",tip:"Common nominalisations: develop→development, analyse→analysis, argue→argument, conclude→conclusion, fail→failure, govern→governance, solve→solution, apply→application, evaluate→evaluation. Academic style strongly prefers these noun forms. Avoid: 'They decided to implement' → 'The implementation of'. But do not over-nominalise — too many nominalisations make writing heavy and difficult to read. Balance nominal and verbal structures."},
  {id:"gi18",title:"Discourse Markers",q:"The study found positive results. ___, further research is needed before drawing conclusions.",opts:["However","Therefore","Moreover","Nevertheless"],ans:3,exp:"'Nevertheless' is a formal concessive adverb meaning 'despite what has just been said' or 'even so'. Here, the study found positive results (positive news), NEVERTHELESS further research is still needed (this is a limitation that must be acknowledged despite the positive findings). 'However' would work too, but 'nevertheless' is stronger — it implies 'despite the promising results, caution is still needed'. 'Therefore' would be wrong — the positive results don't logically lead to needing more research.",tip:"Discourse markers and their precise meanings: HOWEVER = simple contrast, very common. NEVERTHELESS = contrast, but stronger acknowledgement of the previous point ('even so, still'). THEREFORE = logical result/conclusion. MOREOVER/FURTHERMORE = adding a point that strengthens the argument. CONSEQUENTLY = result, more formal than 'so'. NOTWITHSTANDING = despite, very formal legal/academic register. Vary your discourse markers — using only 'however' and 'therefore' makes writing monotonous."},
  {id:"gi19",title:"Subjunctive",q:"It is essential that every student ___ their essay before submission.",opts:["proofread","proofreads","should proofreads","to proofread"],ans:0,exp:"The subjunctive mood is used in formal English after certain expressions that convey necessity, importance, or recommendation. In subjunctive, the verb takes the base form regardless of the subject — even for third person singular: 'It is essential that every student proofread' (NOT 'proofreads'). This seems unusual because in normal present tense, third person adds -s. The subjunctive removes this -s, treating all subjects identically.",tip:"Mandative subjunctive triggers: It is essential/vital/important/necessary/crucial/imperative/recommended + that + subject + BASE VERB (no -s). 'It is recommended that the researcher triangulate their data.' 'It is essential that participants complete the survey.' Alternative: use modal + infinitive: 'Participants should complete the survey.' 'The researcher must triangulate data.' In American English, subjunctive is more commonly used than in British English, which often prefers the modal alternative."},
  {id:"gi20",title:"Mixed Conditionals",q:"If she ___ harder at school, she would be in a better position today.",opts:["studied","had studied","studies","would study"],ans:1,exp:"Mixed conditionals combine a third conditional condition (past hypothetical) with a second conditional result (present hypothetical). 'If she had studied harder at school' (she didn't — past hypothetical), 'she would be in a better position today' (she isn't — present result). This structure is used to show how a past action (or inaction) has consequences that persist in the present. It is more sophisticated than simple second or third conditionals.",tip:"Mixed conditional structure: IF + PAST PERFECT (past hypothetical condition) → WOULD + BASE VERB (present result). Used when: a past decision or action affects the current situation. 'If African countries had maintained stronger institutions after independence, they would be more developed today.' 'If she had taken mathematics seriously, she would now have more career options.' Academic: useful for counterfactual historical and policy analysis."},
  {id:"gi21",title:"Emphasis with 'Do'",q:"Despite the challenges, she ___ achieve her academic goals in the end.",opts:["does","did","has","had"],ans:1,exp:"'Did' as an emphatic auxiliary adds special force to an affirmative statement in the past. Without emphasis: 'She achieved her goals.' With emphasis: 'She did achieve her goals' — implying that despite doubts or obstacles, she genuinely achieved them. 'Do/does' performs the same function in present tense: 'He does work hard' (despite what people might think). This emphatic use is very different from 'did' in questions ('Did she achieve?') and negatives ('She didn't achieve').",tip:"Emphatic do/does/did: DO + base verb (present): 'She does care about her students.' DID + base verb (past): 'He did submit the essay on time.' These structures appear in academic writing to add emphasis and counter potential doubt: 'This study does show significant results, despite the small sample.' 'The data did confirm the hypothesis, although with important caveats.' Use sparingly — overuse loses the emphatic force."},
];

export const VOCAB_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"vi01",word:"Alleviate",ph:"/əˈliːvieɪt/",fr:"Atténuer/Soulager",pos:"verb",def:"To make suffering, a problem, or difficulty less severe.",ex:"Education can ___ poverty by providing people with marketable skills.",opts:["alleviate","aggravate","allocate","alternate"],ans:0,tip:"All + eviate (lighten). To alleviate = to make lighter, to reduce the weight of a problem."},
  {id:"vi02",word:"Sustainable",ph:"/səˈsteɪnəbl/",fr:"Durable",pos:"adjective",def:"Able to be maintained at a certain level without depleting resources.",ex:"The country needs ___ economic policies that protect both growth and the environment.",opts:["sustainable","substantial","susceptible","successive"],ans:0,tip:"Sustain + able. Sustainable = able to sustain itself over time without running out."},
  {id:"vi03",word:"Proliferate",ph:"/prəˈlɪfəreɪt/",fr:"Proliférer",pos:"verb",def:"To increase rapidly in number or spread widely.",ex:"Mobile phone use has ___ across Africa faster than any other technology.",opts:["proliferate","deliberate","exaggerate","collaborate"],ans:0,tip:"Pro (forward) + lifer (life). To proliferate = to grow life rapidly, like cells multiplying."},
  {id:"vi04",word:"Marginalise",ph:"/ˈmɑːdʒɪnəlaɪz/",fr:"Marginaliser",pos:"verb",def:"To treat a group as insignificant or peripheral to mainstream society.",ex:"Economic systems that ___ rural communities contribute to urban migration.",opts:["marginalise","neutralise","capitalise","jeopardise"],ans:0,tip:"Margin + alise. People on the margin are at the edge, excluded from the centre."},
  {id:"vi05",word:"Integrity",ph:"/ɪnˈtegrɪti/",fr:"Intégrité",pos:"noun",def:"The quality of being honest and having strong moral principles.",ex:"Academic ___ requires that students submit only their own original work.",opts:["integrity","identity","intensity","intimacy"],ans:0,tip:"Integer (whole). Integrity = being whole, consistent, and undivided in your values."},
  {id:"vi06",word:"Perpetuate",ph:"/pəˈpetʃueɪt/",fr:"Perpétuer",pos:"verb",def:"To make something continue indefinitely, especially something negative.",ex:"Poverty can ___ itself across generations if education is not accessible.",opts:["perpetuate","evaluate","cultivate","stimulate"],ans:0,tip:"Perpetual + ate. To perpetuate = to make something perpetual (never-ending)."},
  {id:"vi07",word:"Rhetoric",ph:"/ˈretərɪk/",fr:"Rhétorique",pos:"noun",def:"Persuasive language used in speaking or writing; often implies impressive but hollow speech.",ex:"Politicians must translate ___ into concrete policy if they want lasting change.",opts:["rhetoric","historic","sceptic","critic"],ans:0,tip:"Rhet (speech) + oric. Rhetoric = the art of speaking persuasively, sometimes without substance."},
  {id:"vi08",word:"Empirical",ph:"/ɪmˈpɪrɪkəl/",fr:"Empirique",pos:"adjective",def:"Based on observation, experiment, or evidence rather than theory.",ex:"The report requires ___ data, not opinions or assumptions.",opts:["empirical","identical","typical","critical"],ans:0,tip:"Empire (experience). Empirical = based on real experience and evidence, not theory."},
  {id:"vi09",word:"Exacerbate",ph:"/ɪɡˈzæsəbeɪt/",fr:"Exacerber",pos:"verb",def:"To make a problem or negative situation worse.",ex:"Corruption ___ inequality by directing resources away from the poorest citizens.",opts:["exacerbate","accelerate","elaborate","illustrate"],ans:0,tip:"Ex (out) + acerb (bitter). To exacerbate = to make something more bitter/sharp/painful."},
  {id:"vi10",word:"Transparent",ph:"/trænsˈpærənt/",fr:"Transparent",pos:"adjective",def:"Open, honest, and not secretive; easy to understand.",ex:"A ___ government publishes its budget and allows citizens to scrutinise spending.",opts:["transparent","transient","translucent","transcendent"],ans:0,tip:"Trans (through) + parent (visible). Transparent = you can see through it clearly."},
  {id:"vi11",word:"Disproportionate",ph:"/ˌdɪsprəˈpɔːʃənət/",fr:"Disproportionné",pos:"adjective",def:"Too large or too small in comparison to something else.",ex:"Women bear a ___ burden of unpaid domestic work in many African societies.",opts:["disproportionate","inappropriate","approximate","inadequate"],ans:0,tip:"Dis (away from) + proportion. Disproportionate = not in proper proportion, unbalanced."},
  {id:"vi12",word:"Scrutinise",ph:"/ˈskruːtɪnaɪz/",fr:"Examiner attentivement",pos:"verb",def:"To examine or inspect something very carefully.",ex:"Researchers must ___ their data carefully before drawing conclusions.",opts:["scrutinise","recognise","antagonise","authorise"],ans:0,tip:"Scrutin (examine carefully) + ise. To scrutinise = to look very closely and critically."},
  {id:"vi13",word:"Prevalent",ph:"/ˈprevələnt/",fr:"Répandu/Courant",pos:"adjective",def:"Widespread; common in a particular area or among a particular group.",ex:"Malnutrition remains ___ in many rural communities across West Africa.",opts:["prevalent","irrelevant","ambivalent","equivalent"],ans:0,tip:"Prevail + ent. Prevalent = currently prevailing, widespread and common."},
  {id:"vi14",word:"Undermine",ph:"/ˌʌndəˈmaɪn/",fr:"Saper/Compromettre",pos:"verb",def:"To weaken or damage something gradually.",ex:"Corruption ___ public trust in government institutions.",opts:["undermine","determine","examine","combine"],ans:0,tip:"Under + mine (dig). To undermine = to dig under the foundation, weakening it from below."},
  {id:"vi15",word:"Advocate",ph:"/ˈædvəkeɪt/",fr:"Défendre/Préconiser",pos:"verb/noun",def:"To publicly support or recommend a particular cause or policy.",ex:"Many NGOs ___ for greater investment in girls' education.",opts:["advocate","allocate","aggravate","accommodate"],ans:0,tip:"Ad (to) + voc (voice). To advocate = to give your voice to support a cause."},
  {id:"vi16",word:"Disparity",ph:"/dɪˈspærɪti/",fr:"Disparité",pos:"noun",def:"A great difference between things; inequality.",ex:"The ___ in income between urban and rural workers remains a major challenge.",opts:["disparity","similarity","familiarity","popularity"],ans:0,tip:"Dis (apart) + par (equal). Disparity = being apart from equality, a gap."},
  {id:"vi17",word:"Incorporate",ph:"/ɪnˈkɔːpəreɪt/",fr:"Incorporer/Intégrer",pos:"verb",def:"To include something as part of a whole.",ex:"The new curriculum ___ critical thinking and problem-solving skills.",opts:["incorporate","accelerate","deteriorate","collaborate"],ans:0,tip:"In + corp (body). To incorporate = to bring something into the body of something else."},
  {id:"vi18",word:"Coherence",ph:"/kəʊˈhɪərəns/",fr:"Cohérence",pos:"noun",def:"The quality of being logical, consistent, and forming a unified whole.",ex:"The ___ of your argument depends on each paragraph connecting clearly to the next.",opts:["coherence","inference","reference","adherence"],ans:0,tip:"Co (together) + here (stick). Coherence = ideas that stick together in a logical way."},
  {id:"vi19",word:"Catalyst",ph:"/ˈkætəlɪst/",fr:"Catalyseur",pos:"noun",def:"Something that causes or accelerates change.",ex:"The independence movements of the 1960s were a ___ for social reform across Africa.",opts:["catalyst","analyst","specialist","finalist"],ans:0,tip:"From chemistry: a catalyst speeds up a reaction. In society, it triggers rapid change."},
  {id:"vi20",word:"Unprecedented",ph:"/ʌnˈpresɪdentɪd/",fr:"Sans précédent",pos:"adjective",def:"Never having happened or existed before.",ex:"The spread of mobile technology in Africa has been ___.",opts:["unprecedented","unrepresented","unintended","uncontested"],ans:0,tip:"Un (not) + precedent (something that came before). Unprecedented = no precedent exists."},
  {id:"vi21",word:"Holistic",ph:"/hɒˈlɪstɪk/",fr:"Holistique/Global",pos:"adjective",def:"Dealing with something as a whole rather than focusing on individual parts.",ex:"A ___ approach to education considers students' social, emotional, and academic needs.",opts:["holistic","realistic","optimistic","simplistic"],ans:0,tip:"Hol (whole) + istic. Holistic = treating the whole, not just parts."},
];

export const READING_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"ri01",title:"The Legacy of Colonialism in African Education",topic:"Education & History",passage:"The educational systems of most African countries were designed by colonial powers in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. These systems were not built to serve the needs of African populations — they were designed to produce clerks, administrators, and workers for the colonial economy. The curriculum emphasised European history, European languages, and European values while systematically devaluing African knowledge, languages, and traditions.\n\nThis colonial legacy continues to shape education in Africa today. French remains the sole language of instruction in Côte d'Ivoire's schools, despite the fact that most students speak it as a second or third language. Research consistently shows that children learn most effectively in their mother tongue, yet this evidence has largely been ignored in post-colonial educational policy.\n\nScholars like Ngugi wa Thiong'o have argued powerfully that the continued use of European languages in African education represents a form of cultural colonialism that persists long after political independence. They argue that true decolonisation of education requires not only changing what is taught, but fundamentally reconsidering the language in which knowledge is transmitted.",gloss:[{w:"curriculum",d:"the subjects studied in school or university"},{w:"devaluing",d:"treating something as less important or worthy"},{w:"decolonisation",d:"removing the political, cultural or economic effects of colonialism"}],qs:[{q:"What was the original purpose of colonial education systems?",opts:["To promote African culture","To produce workers for the colonial economy","To spread democracy","To teach European languages"],ans:1},{q:"What does Ngugi wa Thiong'o argue?",opts:["French is the best language for education","African languages are inferior","Using European languages is a form of continued colonialism","Schools should teach more science"],ans:2},{q:"What does the passage say about children learning in their mother tongue?",opts:["It is less effective","Research shows it is more effective","It has been widely adopted","It is only good for young children"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri02",title:"Urbanisation and the Future of African Cities",topic:"Society & Development",passage:"Africa is urbanising at a faster rate than any other continent in history. By 2050, the United Nations estimates that more than 60% of Africans will live in cities — a dramatic increase from the current figure of approximately 43%. This urban transition presents both extraordinary opportunities and profound challenges.\n\nOn the positive side, cities are engines of economic growth, innovation, and social change. Urban populations tend to have better access to education, healthcare, and employment. The concentration of people and economic activity in cities enables the kind of specialisation and productivity that drives development.\n\nHowever, rapid and unplanned urbanisation creates serious problems. Many African cities have expanded through the growth of informal settlements — areas characterised by inadequate housing, poor sanitation, limited access to clean water, and a lack of legal security for residents. In Abidjan, it is estimated that more than half the population lives in such areas.\n\nThe central challenge for African urban planners is not to stop urbanisation — which is both inevitable and potentially beneficial — but to manage it in a way that creates inclusive, sustainable, and liveable cities for all residents.",gloss:[{w:"urban transition",d:"the shift from rural to urban living"},{w:"informal settlements",d:"unplanned urban areas with poor infrastructure"},{w:"inclusive",d:"including all people, especially the disadvantaged"}],qs:[{q:"What percentage of Africans will live in cities by 2050?",opts:["43%","More than 60%","75%","50%"],ans:1},{q:"What characterises informal settlements?",opts:["Modern infrastructure","Inadequate housing, poor sanitation, limited water","High-rise buildings","Good schools and hospitals"],ans:1},{q:"What does the author say is the main urban planning challenge?",opts:["Stopping urbanisation","Reducing city populations","Managing urbanisation to create inclusive cities","Building more roads"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri03",title:"The Economics of Climate Change in Africa",topic:"Environment & Economy",passage:"Africa is widely considered the continent most vulnerable to the effects of climate change, despite contributing less than 4% of global greenhouse gas emissions. This profound injustice — being least responsible yet most affected — has become a central argument in international climate negotiations.\n\nThe economic costs of climate change in Africa are already significant. Droughts reduce agricultural yields, threatening food security and rural livelihoods. Extreme weather events destroy infrastructure that has taken decades to build. Rising sea levels threaten coastal cities. The African Development Bank has estimated that climate change could reduce African GDP by between 2% and 4% annually by mid-century without significant adaptation.\n\nAt the same time, Africa has enormous potential to contribute to global climate solutions. The continent possesses vast renewable energy resources — solar, wind, geothermal, and hydroelectric. If developed appropriately, these resources could power Africa's growth while generating clean energy exports.\n\nThe key question is whether wealthy nations will provide the financial support they have promised to help Africa both adapt to climate change and transition to clean energy. So far, the record has been disappointing.",gloss:[{w:"greenhouse gas emissions",d:"gases released by burning fossil fuels that warm the planet"},{w:"adaptation",d:"adjusting to new conditions, especially climate change"},{w:"geothermal",d:"relating to heat produced within the Earth"}],qs:[{q:"What percentage of global emissions does Africa contribute?",opts:["Less than 4%","About 15%","More than 20%","About 10%"],ans:0},{q:"By how much could climate change reduce African GDP annually?",opts:["0.5-1%","2-4%","5-8%","10%"],ans:1},{q:"What does the author say about wealthy nations' climate finance promises?",opts:["They have delivered well","The record has been disappointing","They have exceeded targets","No promises have been made"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri04",title:"Digital Literacy and the Knowledge Economy",topic:"Technology & Education",passage:"The concept of digital literacy — the ability to find, evaluate, create, and communicate information using digital technology — has become essential in the modern knowledge economy. Yet for millions of young Africans, the gap between their digital skills and those required by the labour market remains significant.\n\nThis skills gap has multiple dimensions. At the most basic level, many students lack access to computers and reliable internet connections, making it impossible to develop practical digital skills. But even among those with access, there is a qualitative gap: the ability to use social media platforms is very different from the ability to code, analyse data, or create digital content professionally.\n\nSeveral African countries and organisations are attempting to address this challenge. Rwanda has invested heavily in connecting schools to high-speed internet. The coding bootcamp movement has spread rapidly, with organisations like Andela training software developers across the continent. Companies like Flutterwave and Paystack, founded by young Africans, have demonstrated that world-class technology companies can emerge from the continent.\n\nNevertheless, achieving digital equity — ensuring that all young Africans have the digital skills needed to participate fully in the modern economy — will require sustained investment, policy commitment, and international cooperation.",gloss:[{w:"knowledge economy",d:"an economy based on intellectual skills and information"},{w:"qualitative gap",d:"a difference in quality, not just quantity"},{w:"digital equity",d:"fair access to digital technology and skills for all"}],qs:[{q:"What is digital literacy?",opts:["Using social media","Finding, evaluating, creating and communicating using digital technology","Programming computers","Using smartphones"],ans:1},{q:"What is the qualitative gap mentioned?",opts:["Lack of computers","Difference between using social media and professional digital skills","Slow internet","Cost of devices"],ans:1},{q:"What company is mentioned as an example of African tech success?",opts:["Google","Microsoft","Flutterwave","Samsung"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri05",title:"The Psychology of Poverty",topic:"Society & Health",passage:"Research in behavioural economics has fundamentally changed how we understand poverty. The traditional view held that poverty was primarily the result of poor individual choices — laziness, irresponsibility, or lack of ambition. The emerging consensus, supported by substantial empirical evidence, suggests a very different picture.\n\nSendhil Mullainathan and Eldar Shafir, in their influential book Scarcity, argue that poverty creates a 'bandwidth tax' on the poor. When people are preoccupied with meeting immediate needs — paying rent, finding food, managing debt — cognitive resources that could be devoted to planning, learning, and making good long-term decisions are consumed by the mental effort of managing scarcity. This is not a character defect; it is a predictable psychological response to constraint.\n\nThe policy implications are significant. If poverty impairs cognitive function and decision-making, then approaches that simply provide information or advice to poor people without addressing underlying material conditions are unlikely to succeed. Effective poverty reduction requires addressing structural conditions — access to education, healthcare, stable income, and social protection — not simply changing individual behaviour.",gloss:[{w:"behavioural economics",d:"study of how psychology affects economic decisions"},{w:"bandwidth tax",d:"the mental cost imposed by managing scarcity"},{w:"structural conditions",d:"social and economic systems that shape people's circumstances"}],qs:[{q:"What does the traditional view of poverty emphasise?",opts:["Structural inequality","Poor individual choices","Lack of education","Government failure"],ans:1},{q:"What is a 'bandwidth tax' according to Mullainathan and Shafir?",opts:["A cost of internet access","The mental cost of managing scarcity","A tax on the poor","A financial penalty"],ans:1},{q:"What do the authors suggest for effective poverty reduction?",opts:["More advice for poor people","Changing individual behaviour","Addressing structural conditions","Better information campaigns"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri06",title:"African Literature and Postcolonial Identity",topic:"Culture & Literature",passage:"The literary tradition that emerged in Africa after independence was, in many ways, a project of radical self-definition. Writers like Chinua Achebe, Wole Soyinka, Mariama Bâ, and Camara Laye were not merely writing novels or poetry — they were constructing new narratives of African identity that challenged centuries of misrepresentation by European writers and explorers.\n\nChinua Achebe made this purpose explicit in his famous essay, 'An Image of Africa', in which he criticised Joseph Conrad's Heart of Darkness for its dehumanising portrayal of Africans. Achebe argued that literature has the power to affirm or deny the humanity of entire peoples, and that African writers had a responsibility to reclaim their own stories.\n\nThis postcolonial literary tradition continues today, with contemporary African writers like Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie, NoViolet Bulawayo, and Alain Mabanckou reaching global audiences. Adichie's TED talk 'The Danger of a Single Story' — which has been viewed over 25 million times — powerfully articulates the damage done when any people or continent is reduced to a single, simplified narrative.",gloss:[{w:"self-definition",d:"the act of defining one's own identity"},{w:"misrepresentation",d:"an inaccurate or misleading description"},{w:"postcolonial",d:"relating to the period after colonial rule ended"}],qs:[{q:"What was the purpose of post-independence African literature?",opts:["To entertain European readers","To challenge misrepresentation and define African identity","To translate African languages","To promote tourism"],ans:1},{q:"What did Achebe criticise in his essay?",opts:["African governments","European education","Conrad's dehumanising portrayal of Africans","Modern African writers"],ans:2},{q:"What is 'The Danger of a Single Story' about?",opts:["African history","The damage of reducing any people to one simplified narrative","Nigerian literature","Colonial education"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri07",title:"Microfinance and Women's Empowerment",topic:"Economy & Society",passage:"Microfinance — the provision of small loans and financial services to people who lack access to conventional banking — has been promoted as a powerful tool for poverty reduction and women's empowerment since the 1970s, when Muhammad Yunus founded the Grameen Bank in Bangladesh.\n\nIn Africa, microfinance institutions have proliferated, with millions of women accessing small loans to start or expand businesses. Proponents argue that when women control financial resources, they invest more in their children's education and health than men typically do, creating positive effects that extend across generations.\n\nHowever, critical research has complicated this optimistic picture. Some studies have found that microfinance loans can trap borrowers in cycles of debt, particularly when interest rates are high. Others have found that the transformative effects on women's empowerment are more limited than initially claimed — in many cases, women take out loans but male family members control how the money is used.\n\nThe consensus today is more nuanced: microfinance can be a valuable tool in the right conditions, but it is not a sufficient substitute for structural changes in gender equality, legal rights, and access to education.",gloss:[{w:"microfinance",d:"provision of small financial services to low-income people"},{w:"proponents",d:"people who support a particular idea or policy"},{w:"nuanced",d:"taking account of fine distinctions; not simplistic"}],qs:[{q:"Who founded the Grameen Bank?",opts:["Nelson Mandela","Muhammad Yunus","Wangari Maathai","Kofi Annan"],ans:1},{q:"What do proponents claim about women controlling financial resources?",opts:["Women spend money on luxuries","Women invest more in children's education and health","Women save more than men","Women start bigger businesses"],ans:1},{q:"What does the current consensus say about microfinance?",opts:["It solves all poverty","It always empowers women","It is a useful tool but insufficient alone","It should be banned"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri08",title:"Democracy and Development in Africa",topic:"Politics",passage:"A long-running debate in development studies concerns the relationship between democracy and economic development. Some scholars argue that democracy is a prerequisite for sustainable development: without accountability and the protection of rights, development gains are easily reversed by corrupt or authoritarian leaders. Others contend that economic development can and should precede democratisation — pointing to East Asian developmental states like South Korea and Singapore as evidence.\n\nThe African evidence is mixed. Democracies like Botswana and Cape Verde have maintained consistent growth and development. Yet some authoritarian regimes have also delivered economic progress, at least in the short term. The resource curse theory suggests that oil-rich African states are particularly prone to authoritarianism, as governments can fund themselves from oil revenues without needing to tax — and therefore be accountable to — their citizens.\n\nMost contemporary scholars emphasise that democracy and development are mutually reinforcing when both are functioning effectively. A democracy with strong institutions — independent courts, free press, professional civil service — is better equipped to manage resources wisely and respond to citizens' needs than an authoritarian system that depends on personal loyalty rather than institutional capacity.",gloss:[{w:"prerequisite",d:"something required before something else can happen"},{w:"authoritarian",d:"favoring complete obedience to authority, limiting individual freedom"},{w:"resource curse",d:"the paradox of countries with abundant natural resources having poor development"}],qs:[{q:"What does the 'resource curse theory' suggest?",opts:["Natural resources always benefit development","Oil-rich states tend toward authoritarianism because they don't need to tax citizens","Democracy requires natural resources","Development causes democracy"],ans:1},{q:"Which countries are given as examples of successful democratic development?",opts:["Nigeria and Angola","South Korea and Singapore","Botswana and Cape Verde","South Africa and Kenya"],ans:2},{q:"What do most contemporary scholars emphasise?",opts:["Democracy must come before development","Development must come before democracy","Democracy and development are mutually reinforcing","Neither democracy nor development matters"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri09",title:"The Science of Learning",topic:"Education & Psychology",passage:"Cognitive science has produced important insights about how learning actually happens that are often poorly understood by teachers and students alike. Several findings challenge common assumptions about study habits and teaching methods.\n\nFirst, spaced repetition — reviewing material at increasing intervals — is significantly more effective than 'massed practice' or 'cramming'. Memory research shows that we forget most new information rapidly unless we revisit it at strategic intervals, a phenomenon known as the spacing effect.\n\nSecond, retrieval practice — testing yourself on material rather than re-reading it — dramatically improves long-term retention. When students try to recall information, even if they fail, the memory trace is strengthened in a way that passive re-reading cannot achieve.\n\nThird, interleaving — mixing different topics or types of problems during study — produces better long-term learning than blocked practice, even though it feels harder and less productive in the moment. This counter-intuitive finding suggests that students' perceptions of what constitutes effective study are often inaccurate.\n\nThese insights have profound implications for how universities and schools should structure their curricula and assessments.",gloss:[{w:"spaced repetition",d:"reviewing material at increasing time intervals"},{w:"retrieval practice",d:"testing yourself to strengthen memory"},{w:"interleaving",d:"mixing different topics during a study session"}],qs:[{q:"What is the spacing effect?",opts:["Studying in large spaces","Forgetting information unless reviewed at intervals","Learning one topic at a time","Taking breaks while studying"],ans:1},{q:"Why is retrieval practice more effective than re-reading?",opts:["It is faster","Trying to recall strengthens memory traces","It is easier","It covers more material"],ans:1},{q:"What does interleaving involve?",opts:["Studying one subject for a long time","Mixing different topics during study","Taking regular breaks","Group study sessions"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri10",title:"Food Security in West Africa",topic:"Health & Environment",passage:"Food security — defined by the UN as a situation in which all people have physical, social, and economic access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food — remains a critical challenge across West Africa. Despite the region's vast agricultural potential, millions of people experience chronic food insecurity.\n\nMultiple factors contribute to this paradox. Climate change is making rainfall less predictable, threatening rainfed agriculture upon which most smallholder farmers depend. Land degradation — caused by deforestation, overgrazing, and unsustainable farming practices — reduces agricultural productivity over time. Post-harvest losses, which can amount to 30-40% of production in some areas due to poor storage and transport infrastructure, represent an enormous waste of food that has already been grown.\n\nPolicy responses have often focused on increasing production, but researchers increasingly argue that a more holistic approach is needed. Reducing post-harvest losses, improving market access for smallholder farmers, strengthening social protection for the most vulnerable, and adapting agricultural systems to climate change are all essential components of a comprehensive food security strategy.",gloss:[{w:"food security",d:"reliable access to sufficient, safe, nutritious food"},{w:"smallholder farmers",d:"farmers who cultivate small areas of land"},{w:"post-harvest losses",d:"food lost after harvesting due to poor storage or transport"}],qs:[{q:"How are post-harvest losses defined in the passage?",opts:["Food wasted by consumers","Food lost after harvesting due to poor storage/transport","Food destroyed by pests","Food that fails to grow"],ans:1},{q:"What percentage of production can be lost post-harvest?",opts:["5-10%","10-20%","30-40%","50-60%"],ans:2},{q:"What do researchers increasingly argue is needed for food security?",opts:["Only increasing production","A holistic approach including reducing losses and improving market access","Only better climate policies","Only more foreign aid"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri11",title:"The Role of the African Union",topic:"Politics & Development",passage:"The African Union (AU), established in 2002 as the successor to the Organisation of African Unity, represents the most ambitious attempt in history to create a unified political and economic framework for the African continent. With 55 member states, it is the world's largest regional organisation by membership.\n\nThe AU's ambitious agenda includes the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA), launched in 2021, which aims to create a single market covering 1.3 billion people with a combined GDP of over $3 trillion. If fully implemented, the AfCFTA would be the world's largest free trade area and could significantly accelerate African economic integration.\n\nHowever, the AU faces significant institutional challenges. It is chronically underfunded — heavily dependent on contributions from external donors, including the European Union, for a significant portion of its operational budget. Its decisions are often not binding on member states, limiting its ability to enforce commitments on issues like democracy, human rights, and economic reform. Critics argue that until the AU develops genuine financial independence and enforcement capacity, it will remain more aspiration than institution.",gloss:[{w:"AfCFTA",d:"African Continental Free Trade Area"},{w:"binding",d:"legally obligatory; must be obeyed"},{w:"aspiration",d:"a hope or ambition to achieve something"}],qs:[{q:"When was the African Union established?",opts:["1963","1991","2002","2010"],ans:2},{q:"What is the AfCFTA?",opts:["A political union","A military alliance","A single market for Africa","An aid organisation"],ans:2},{q:"What is a key weakness of the AU according to critics?",opts:["Too many member states","Lack of financial independence and enforcement capacity","Located in the wrong country","Too focused on trade"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri12",title:"Youth Mental Health in Africa",topic:"Health & Society",passage:"Mental health disorders affect approximately 1 in 5 people worldwide, yet in Africa, fewer than 1 in 10 people with a mental health condition receive treatment. This treatment gap reflects a confluence of factors: severe shortage of mental health professionals, inadequate funding, deeply entrenched stigma, and healthcare systems that have historically prioritised infectious diseases.\n\nYoung people are particularly vulnerable. Adolescence and early adulthood are the periods when most mental health disorders first manifest. The pressures facing young Africans today — economic uncertainty, urbanisation, social media, academic pressure, and the psychological effects of poverty — create significant mental health burdens.\n\nYet the cultural context complicates diagnosis and treatment. In many African communities, mental illness is explained through spiritual or supernatural frameworks rather than biomedical ones. Healers and religious leaders are often the first — and sometimes the only — recourse for those experiencing mental distress. Effective mental health interventions must engage with these cultural realities rather than dismissing them.\n\nSome promising models exist. Community mental health workers, trained to provide basic psychological support at primary healthcare level, have shown effectiveness in Ethiopia and Uganda. Integrating mental health into existing community systems, rather than relying exclusively on specialised facilities, may be the most realistic path forward.",gloss:[{w:"confluence",d:"the coming together of several factors"},{w:"manifest",d:"to become visible or apparent"},{w:"biomedical",d:"relating to conventional Western medical science"}],qs:[{q:"What fraction of Africans with mental health conditions receive treatment?",opts:["1 in 2","1 in 3","1 in 10","1 in 20"],ans:2},{q:"What cultural factor complicates mental health treatment in Africa?",opts:["Language barriers","Mental illness explained through spiritual frameworks","Lack of families","Cost of treatment"],ans:1},{q:"What promising model is mentioned?",opts:["Building more hospitals","Importing foreign doctors","Community mental health workers","Online therapy"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri13",title:"Trade, Aid, and African Development",topic:"Economy",passage:"The debate between trade and aid as engines of African development has occupied economists and policymakers for decades. Aid sceptics, most prominently the Zambian economist Dambisa Moyo in her controversial book Dead Aid, argue that foreign aid has made Africa worse off by creating dependency, undermining local markets, and funding corrupt governments. They advocate instead for greater African integration into global trade as the path to sustainable development.\n\nProponents of aid counter that while badly designed aid has indeed caused harm, well-targeted interventions — particularly in health, education, and humanitarian response — have saved millions of lives and created conditions for long-term development. They argue that the extreme poverty and infrastructure deficits facing many African countries make it unrealistic to expect private investment or trade alone to solve these challenges in the short term.\n\nThe most sophisticated contemporary view recognises that neither trade nor aid alone is sufficient. What matters more than the instrument — aid or trade — is the quality of governance, the strength of institutions, and the coherence of development strategies. Countries that have used external resources strategically to build domestic capacity have generally outperformed those that have relied passively on either aid or trade revenues.",gloss:[{w:"dependency",d:"relying on something or someone excessively"},{w:"infrastructure deficits",d:"lack of basic systems like roads, electricity, and water"},{w:"coherence",d:"being logical and consistent"}],qs:[{q:"What does Dambisa Moyo argue in Dead Aid?",opts:["Aid has helped Africa greatly","Aid has made Africa worse off","Trade is impossible for Africa","Aid should increase"],ans:1},{q:"What do aid proponents say about well-targeted aid?",opts:["It creates dependency","It has saved millions of lives","It is always ineffective","It replaces trade"],ans:1},{q:"What does the sophisticated contemporary view emphasise?",opts:["Aid is always better","Trade is always better","Quality of governance and institutions matters most","Neither aid nor trade works"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri14",title:"The Environment-Conflict Nexus",topic:"Environment & Politics",passage:"A growing body of research examines the links between environmental degradation and armed conflict. The hypothesis that climate change and resource scarcity can trigger or intensify violent conflict has gained considerable attention, particularly in the context of the Sahel region of West Africa.\n\nThe conflict in the Lake Chad Basin, which has displaced millions of people and destabilised parts of Nigeria, Niger, Chad, and Cameroon, is frequently cited as an example of environment-conflict linkages. The lake has shrunk by approximately 90% since the 1960s, reducing the agricultural and fishing livelihoods of millions of people and creating competition over increasingly scarce resources.\n\nHowever, researchers caution against simplistic environmental determinism — the idea that environmental stress automatically produces conflict. The relationship is mediated by political, social, and economic factors. Communities facing identical environmental pressures may respond very differently depending on governance quality, levels of inequality, cultural conflict resolution mechanisms, and external interventions.\n\nEffective responses to environment-conflict risks therefore require integrated strategies that address both the environmental drivers and the governance failures that prevent communities from adapting peacefully to environmental change.",gloss:[{w:"environmental determinism",d:"the theory that environment automatically determines human behaviour"},{w:"mediated",d:"influenced or modified by intervening factors"},{w:"integrated strategies",d:"approaches that combine multiple different elements"}],qs:[{q:"By how much has Lake Chad shrunk since the 1960s?",opts:["30%","50%","75%","90%"],ans:3},{q:"What do researchers caution against?",opts:["Studying environment-conflict links","Simplistic environmental determinism","Addressing governance failures","International cooperation"],ans:1},{q:"What do effective responses require according to the passage?",opts:["Only environmental solutions","Only military responses","Integrated strategies addressing environment and governance","Relocating affected populations"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri15",title:"Language and Power in Africa",topic:"Culture & Politics",passage:"Language is never politically neutral. The languages that societies choose — or are forced — to use in education, government, and public life reflect and reinforce power relations. In Africa, the continued dominance of European languages in formal institutions is both a product of colonial history and an ongoing mechanism of social stratification.\n\nFluency in French, English, or Portuguese remains a powerful determinant of life chances in most African countries. Access to higher education, formal employment, and political participation is substantially mediated by proficiency in the former colonial language. This creates a systematic disadvantage for those — typically from poorer and more rural backgrounds — who have limited exposure to the colonial language in early childhood.\n\nAt the same time, the picture is complicated by the multilingual realities of African societies. Most Africans speak several languages: a mother tongue, one or more regional languages, and the official European language. This multilingualism is a cognitive and cultural asset, but it is rarely celebrated or systematically developed by educational systems that treat the colonial language as the only legitimate medium of instruction.\n\nThe challenge for African language policy is to find approaches that acknowledge the practical importance of international languages while genuinely valuing and developing the full richness of Africa's linguistic heritage.",gloss:[{w:"stratification",d:"the arrangement of society into different social levels"},{w:"proficiency",d:"a high degree of skill or competence"},{w:"linguistic heritage",d:"the languages inherited from previous generations"}],qs:[{q:"What does the passage say about language in Africa?",opts:["All languages are equally valued","European languages dominate formal institutions","African languages are disappearing","Language is not political"],ans:1},{q:"How does the passage describe African multilingualism?",opts:["A problem for education","A cognitive and cultural asset","Not relevant to development","A sign of confusion"],ans:1},{q:"What is the language policy challenge described?",opts:["Choosing one official language","Eliminating colonial languages","Acknowledging international languages while valuing linguistic heritage","Teaching only African languages"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri16",title:"Philanthropy and Development in Africa",topic:"Economy & Society",passage:"In recent decades, large-scale philanthropy has become an increasingly significant actor in African development. Foundations like the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, the Mo Ibrahim Foundation, and the Tony Elumelu Foundation invest billions of dollars annually in health, education, agriculture, and entrepreneurship across the continent.\n\nProponents argue that private philanthropy can operate with greater flexibility and innovation than government aid — able to take risks, experiment, and respond quickly to emerging needs. The Gates Foundation's investment in malaria vaccines and polio eradication has saved millions of lives in ways that no government programme could have achieved at equivalent speed.\n\nCritics, however, raise important concerns about accountability and power. Large foundations are accountable primarily to their donors, not to the African communities they serve. This creates a risk that philanthropic priorities reflect the interests and assumptions of wealthy donors rather than the genuine needs and aspirations of African people. The Nobel economist Angus Deaton has argued that large-scale philanthropy can displace local institutions and distort national policy priorities.\n\nThe most effective philanthropic interventions appear to be those that work in genuine partnership with local organisations, build local capacity rather than substituting for it, and explicitly aim to make themselves redundant by strengthening domestic systems.",gloss:[{w:"philanthropy",d:"charitable work by the very wealthy"},{w:"eradication",d:"complete elimination of a disease"},{w:"displace",d:"to push aside or take the place of"}],qs:[{q:"What advantage do proponents claim for private philanthropy?",opts:["It is accountable to governments","It has more money than aid","It can operate with greater flexibility and innovation","It replaces government completely"],ans:2},{q:"What does Angus Deaton argue about large-scale philanthropy?",opts:["It always helps development","It can displace local institutions","It should increase","It has no effect"],ans:1},{q:"What characterises the most effective philanthropic interventions?",opts:["Spending the most money","Working without local partners","Building local capacity and aiming to become redundant","Focusing only on health"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri17",title:"The Cocoa Value Chain",topic:"Economy & Côte d'Ivoire",passage:"The global cocoa value chain illustrates one of the central paradoxes of African economic development: the continent that produces the raw material for the world's most beloved confection captures only a tiny fraction of the wealth it generates. Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana together produce more than 60% of the world's cocoa, yet most of the value added — in processing, manufacturing, marketing, and retail — occurs in Europe and North America.\n\nThis distribution of value along the chain is not accidental. It reflects historical trade relationships established during the colonial period, when African territories were integrated into the global economy as exporters of raw materials and importers of manufactured goods. Structural adjustment programmes in the 1980s and 1990s further entrenched this pattern by requiring African countries to reduce tariffs that might have protected domestic processing industries.\n\nRecent years have seen efforts to change this dynamic. Both Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana have announced policies to process a greater share of their cocoa domestically before export. Grinding capacity in both countries has increased significantly. However, the cocoa multinationals that dominate global processing have resisted these moves, and the political and economic obstacles to genuine value addition remain substantial.",gloss:[{w:"value chain",d:"all the stages from raw material to final consumer product"},{w:"value added",d:"the extra value created at each stage of production"},{w:"structural adjustment",d:"economic reforms required by international lenders in the 1980s-90s"}],qs:[{q:"What percentage of world cocoa do Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana produce?",opts:["30%","More than 60%","45%","75%"],ans:1},{q:"Where does most value addition in cocoa occur?",opts:["In Africa","In Asia","In Europe and North America","Equally distributed"],ans:2},{q:"What recent changes have occurred?",opts:["African countries stopped producing cocoa","More domestic processing has been developed","Multinationals moved to Africa","Cocoa prices doubled"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri18",title:"Higher Education in Africa",topic:"Education",passage:"African higher education systems face a complex set of challenges that are both a reflection of the continent's development constraints and a barrier to overcoming them. Enrolment rates, though growing, remain far below global averages: only about 9% of eligible Africans attend university, compared to 38% globally and over 70% in high-income countries.\n\nFunding is a chronic problem. Most African universities are heavily dependent on government funding, which is often insufficient and unpredictable. Brain drain — the emigration of educated professionals — compounds the challenge: African universities train talented graduates who then seek opportunities abroad, depriving the continent of the human capital it needs.\n\nYet there are reasons for cautious optimism. A new generation of African universities — including the African Leadership University, Strathmore University in Kenya, and the African Institute for Mathematical Sciences — are experimenting with innovative models that emphasise entrepreneurship, critical thinking, and African-centred perspectives. Mobile learning platforms are extending access to millions who cannot attend traditional universities. And the recognition that human capital development is central to Africa's economic transformation is creating new political will for investment in higher education.",gloss:[{w:"enrolment rates",d:"the percentage of eligible people attending school or university"},{w:"brain drain",d:"emigration of educated or skilled people"},{w:"human capital",d:"the skills and knowledge of a population"}],qs:[{q:"What percentage of eligible Africans attend university?",opts:["38%","About 9%","25%","70%"],ans:1},{q:"What is 'brain drain'?",opts:["Students failing exams","Educated professionals emigrating","Lack of university funding","Poor teaching quality"],ans:1},{q:"What do new African universities like African Leadership University emphasise?",opts:["Traditional academic subjects only","European perspectives","Entrepreneurship, critical thinking, and African-centred perspectives","Medical training"],ans:2}]},
  {id:"ri19",title:"Inequality and Social Mobility",topic:"Society & Economy",passage:"Economic inequality in Africa has reached levels that threaten both social cohesion and long-term development. While significant progress has been made in reducing extreme poverty over the past two decades, the benefits of growth have been distributed very unevenly. According to Oxfam, Africa's richest 1% now holds more wealth than the bottom 70% of the population.\n\nHigh inequality is not merely a moral concern — it has serious practical consequences. Research consistently shows that societies with high levels of inequality have lower social mobility: the connection between a parent's income and a child's eventual income is stronger in unequal societies. This means that where you are born, not how hard you work or how talented you are, largely determines your economic outcomes.\n\nThe drivers of inequality in Africa are multiple: unequal access to quality education, land ownership concentration, tax evasion by wealthy elites, inadequate labour market regulation, and the failure to invest sufficiently in social protection systems. Addressing inequality requires a comprehensive package of policy interventions — from progressive taxation and land reform to universal education and healthcare — that many governments have been reluctant to pursue.",gloss:[{w:"social cohesion",d:"the bonds that hold a society together"},{w:"social mobility",d:"the ability to move between social classes"},{w:"progressive taxation",d:"taxing higher incomes at higher rates"}],qs:[{q:"What does Oxfam report about Africa's wealthiest 1%?",opts:["They pay the most taxes","They hold more wealth than the bottom 70%","They invest in education","They donate to the poor"],ans:1},{q:"What does research show about inequality and social mobility?",opts:["High inequality increases social mobility","High inequality reduces social mobility","They are unrelated","Social mobility is always low"],ans:1},{q:"What are some drivers of inequality mentioned?",opts:["Too many universities","Unequal education access, tax evasion, inadequate labour regulation","Too many foreign investors","Religious differences"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri20",title:"Artificial Intelligence and African Development",topic:"Technology",passage:"Artificial intelligence represents one of the most significant technological shifts of the twenty-first century, with profound implications for economies and societies worldwide. For Africa, the question is whether AI will deepen existing inequalities or create new opportunities for development.\n\nThe pessimistic scenario is concerning. AI-driven automation threatens to eliminate many of the low-skill manufacturing jobs that have historically served as a pathway out of poverty for developing countries. The comparative advantage in cheap labour that helped East Asia develop may not be available to Africa in an era of automated production.\n\nHowever, the optimistic scenario offers possibilities. AI applications in agriculture — precision farming, disease detection in crops, weather prediction — could significantly increase productivity for smallholder farmers. In healthcare, AI diagnostic tools are already showing promise in detecting diseases like malaria, tuberculosis, and diabetic retinopathy from basic images in settings with few doctors. In education, adaptive learning platforms can personalise instruction for millions of students.\n\nThe extent to which Africa captures the benefits rather than suffers the costs of AI will depend critically on investment in digital infrastructure, AI education and research capacity, and international governance frameworks that ensure developing countries have a voice in how this transformative technology is regulated.",gloss:[{w:"automation",d:"using machines and AI to perform tasks previously done by humans"},{w:"precision farming",d:"using technology to optimise agricultural production"},{w:"adaptive learning",d:"educational technology that adjusts to individual learners"}],qs:[{q:"What is the pessimistic scenario regarding AI and Africa?",opts:["AI will create too many jobs","AI automation may eliminate low-skill manufacturing jobs","AI is too expensive for Africa","AI will harm agriculture"],ans:1},{q:"How is AI showing promise in African healthcare?",opts:["Replacing all doctors","Building hospitals","Detecting diseases from images in low-resource settings","Training nurses"],ans:2},{q:"What will determine Africa's ability to benefit from AI?",opts:["Oil revenues","Investment in digital infrastructure and AI education","Military strength","Population size"],ans:1}]},
  {id:"ri21",title:"Sports Diplomacy and Soft Power",topic:"Culture & Politics",passage:"Sport has long served as a vehicle for political expression and international relations. The Olympic boycotts of the Cold War era, the role of cricket in India-Pakistan relations, and Nelson Mandela's strategic use of the 1995 Rugby World Cup to build post-apartheid national unity in South Africa all demonstrate the political dimensions of sport at their most explicit.\n\nFor African countries, sporting success has often provided a rare opportunity to project a positive image internationally and build national pride domestically. Didier Drogba's international career not only brought attention to Côte d'Ivoire but was credited with helping maintain a ceasefire during the country's civil conflict in 2005, when he appealed directly to Ivorians to lay down their weapons after the national team qualified for the World Cup.\n\nMore broadly, the global spread of African athletes into the highest levels of European football, athletics, basketball, and other sports has created a form of soft power — cultural influence that operates not through coercion but through attraction and admiration. African players like Mohamed Salah in football and Eliud Kipchoge in athletics have generated enormous goodwill for Egypt and Kenya respectively, in ways that diplomacy and foreign aid rarely achieve.",gloss:[{w:"soft power",d:"influence through culture and attraction rather than force"},{w:"ceasefire",d:"an agreement to stop fighting temporarily"},{w:"apartheid",d:"South Africa's former system of racial segregation"}],qs:[{q:"What did Didier Drogba do during Côte d'Ivoire's civil conflict?",opts:["Led a peace negotiation","Appealed for Ivorians to stop fighting after World Cup qualification","Organized a charity match","Left Côte d'Ivoire"],ans:1},{q:"How did Mandela use the 1995 Rugby World Cup?",opts:["To punish opponents","To build post-apartheid national unity","To promote tourism","To raise money"],ans:1},{q:"What is 'soft power'?",opts:["Military strength","Economic sanctions","Cultural influence through attraction and admiration","Political alliances"],ans:2}]},
];

export const MISTAKES_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"mi01",title:"'Due to' vs 'Because of' vs 'Due to the fact that'",fr:"À cause de / En raison de",wrong:"Due to she was late, she missed the beginning of the lecture.",right:"Because she was late, she missed the beginning of the lecture.",rule:"'Due to' and 'owing to' are prepositional phrases that must be followed by a noun or noun phrase, not a full clause (subject + verb). This is one of the most common formal English errors in student essays. To introduce a clause giving a reason, use 'because', 'since', or 'as'. A useful test: if you can replace 'due to' with 'caused by' and the sentence still makes sense, the noun usage is correct: 'The failure was due to poor planning' (caused by poor planning = correct). 'She failed due to she was late' cannot work with 'caused by', so 'because' is needed.",ex:[{w:"Due to the exam was difficult, many students failed.",r:"Because the exam was difficult, many students failed."},{w:"She was absent due to she was ill.",r:"She was absent because she was ill. / She was absent due to illness."}]},
  {id:"mi02",title:"'However' — punctuation and position",fr:"Cependant / Néanmoins",wrong:"The project was interesting, however it was very challenging to complete.",right:"The project was interesting; however, it was very challenging to complete.",rule:"'However' is a conjunctive adverb, not a coordinating conjunction. This means it cannot join two independent clauses with only a comma — doing so creates a comma splice, one of the most serious punctuation errors in academic writing. 'However' must be preceded by a full stop (creating two separate sentences) or a semicolon (a stronger connector that shows the two clauses are closely related). Both are correct; a semicolon is preferred in academic writing when the contrast between the two clauses is particularly close. Always place a comma after 'However' at the start of a clause.",ex:[{w:"She worked hard, however she didn't pass.",r:"She worked hard; however, she didn't pass."},{w:"The results were positive, however more research is needed.",r:"The results were positive. However, more research is needed."}]},
  {id:"mi03",title:"Misuse of 'According to'",fr:"Selon / D'après",wrong:"According to my opinion, education should be free.",right:"In my opinion, education should be free.",rule:"'According to' is an attribution phrase used to introduce a claim, fact, or opinion from an external source: a person, a text, a study, or an institution. It can NEVER introduce your own opinion because you cannot be an 'external source' of your own view. This is a very common error in student essays and in professional writing by French speakers (French uses 'selon moi' naturally). For your own opinion, use: 'In my opinion...', 'In my view...', 'I argue that...', 'I contend that...', 'From my perspective...'. In academic writing, it is usually better to use first-person argument ('I argue') than hedged opinion expressions.",ex:[{w:"According to me, the policy is wrong.",r:"In my opinion, the policy is wrong."},{w:"According to my view, this approach is flawed.",r:"From my perspective, this approach is flawed."}]},
  {id:"mi04",title:"'Sensible' vs 'Sensitive'",fr:"Sensible (French) ≠ Sensible (English)",wrong:"She is a very sensible person — she cries easily.",right:"She is a very sensitive person — she cries easily.",rule:"'Sensible' and 'sensitive' are classic false friends between English and French. French 'sensible' = English 'sensitive' (easily affected emotionally or physically: sensitive to cold, sensitive about criticism). English 'sensible' = French 'raisonnable' or 'sense' (showing good judgment, practical, reasonable: a sensible decision, sensible shoes). When a French speaker describes an emotionally responsive person as 'sensible' in English, the English speaker understands them as 'reasonable' — the opposite of the intended meaning. Always use 'sensitive' for emotional responsiveness.",ex:[{w:"He is sensible about criticism and gets upset easily.",r:"He is sensitive about criticism and gets upset easily."},{w:"That was a sensible decision — very emotional.",r:"That was a sensitive decision — very emotional."}]},
  {id:"mi05",title:"Dangling Participles",fr:"Participes suspendus",wrong:"Having studied hard, the exam seemed easy.",right:"Having studied hard, she found the exam easy.",rule:"A participial phrase (beginning with a verb's -ing or -ed form) must logically refer to the grammatical subject of the main clause that follows it. In 'Having studied hard, the exam seemed easy', the participle 'having studied' has no stated subject — and the grammatical subject of the main clause is 'the exam', which cannot study. This is called a dangling participle (or dangling modifier). The fix is to ensure the subject of the participial phrase is the same as the subject of the main clause: 'Having studied hard, she found the exam easy.' In academic writing, dangling participles seriously undermine credibility.",ex:[{w:"Walking to the library, it started raining.",r:"Walking to the library, she got caught in the rain."},{w:"Having read the article, the conclusions were clear.",r:"Having read the article, I found the conclusions clear."}]},
  {id:"mi06",title:"'Affect' vs 'Effect'",fr:"Affecter / Effet",wrong:"The new policy will effect the lives of thousands of students.",right:"The new policy will affect the lives of thousands of students.",rule:"'Affect' and 'effect' are among the most commonly confused words in English. The key distinction: AFFECT is almost always a VERB meaning to have an impact on: 'Poverty affects health outcomes.' EFFECT is almost always a NOUN meaning a result or outcome: 'Poverty has serious effects on health.' The rare exception: 'to effect change' (formal verb meaning 'to bring about'): 'The reform effected significant change.' A simple test: if you can replace the word with 'impact on', use 'affect' (verb). If you can replace it with 'result' or 'outcome', use 'effect' (noun).",ex:[{w:"Pollution has a serious affect on public health.",r:"Pollution has a serious effect on public health."},{w:"How will the new law effect students?",r:"How will the new law affect students?"}]},
  {id:"mi07",title:"Overuse of 'Very' in Academic Writing",fr:"Très / Vraiment",wrong:"Climate change is a very very important problem that is very dangerous.",right:"Climate change is an extremely serious problem with potentially catastrophic consequences.",rule:"'Very' is one of the weakest intensifiers in English — it adds emphasis but conveys no specific information about degree. In academic writing, it should almost always be replaced by a more precise and stronger expression. The specific alternative depends on the context: 'very important' → crucial, critical, fundamental, essential, paramount. 'Very common' → prevalent, widespread, ubiquitous. 'Very poor' → severely disadvantaged, deeply impoverished. 'Very different' → markedly different, substantially distinct. Strong, precise vocabulary demonstrates command of academic register and makes arguments more persuasive.",ex:[{w:"This is a very big problem for very poor communities.",r:"This is a critical challenge for severely disadvantaged communities."},{w:"The results were very good.",r:"The results were remarkably positive / highly encouraging."}]},
  {id:"mi08",title:"'Composed of' vs 'Comprises'",fr:"Composé de / Comprend",wrong:"The committee is comprised of five members.",right:"The committee comprises five members. / The committee is composed of five members.",rule:"The verb 'comprise' means 'to consist of' or 'to include' and is already active — it does not need 'of'. The passive construction 'is comprised of' treats 'comprise' as if it were 'composed', but this is widely considered incorrect in careful formal usage. Use either: 'comprises' (active, no 'of') — 'The study comprises three phases', or 'is composed of' (passive) — 'The study is composed of three phases'. Both are correct. 'Is comprised of' is increasingly common in informal usage but should be avoided in academic writing.",ex:[{w:"The report is comprised of three sections.",r:"The report comprises three sections. / The report is composed of three sections."},{w:"The team is comprised of experts from five countries.",r:"The team comprises experts from five countries."}]},
  {id:"mi09",title:"'Raise' vs 'Rise'",fr:"Élever / S'élever",wrong:"The cost of living has raised significantly in recent years.",right:"The cost of living has risen significantly in recent years.",rule:"'Rise' and 'raise' look similar but follow completely different grammatical rules. RISE is intransitive — it does not take a direct object. Things rise by themselves: prices rise, temperatures rise, unemployment rises. Forms: rise-rose-risen. RAISE is transitive — it requires a direct object. Someone raises something: the government raises taxes, researchers raise a question, parents raise children. Forms: raise-raised-raised. The error 'prices raised' confuses the intransitive rise with the transitive raise. In academic writing, this error is particularly visible: 'inequality has risen' (intransitive) vs 'the policy raised inequality' (transitive).",ex:[{w:"The government raised taxes and prices rose as a result.",r:"The government raised taxes and prices rose as a result. ✅ (Both correct)"},{w:"Unemployment has raised due to the crisis.",r:"Unemployment has risen due to the crisis."}]},
  {id:"mi10",title:"Incorrect Use of 'Whereas'",fr:"Alors que / Tandis que",wrong:"She studies medicine whereas she wants to help people.",right:"She studies medicine because she wants to help people.",rule:"'Whereas' is a formal conjunction used to draw a contrast between two directly opposing or different facts. The contrast must be genuine and specific: 'Urban poverty rates are declining, whereas rural rates are increasing.' It does NOT mean 'because', 'since', or 'given that'. These causal connectors have completely different functions. A test for correct use: both clauses joined by 'whereas' should be factually true and directly contrasting. If removing 'whereas' and replacing it with 'because' makes sense, then 'whereas' is being used incorrectly.",ex:[{w:"He is good at science whereas he works very hard.",r:"He is good at science because he works very hard."},{w:"Urban areas are wealthy whereas rural areas are poor.",r:"Urban areas are wealthy whereas rural areas are poor. ✅"}]},
  {id:"mi11",title:"'Principal' vs 'Principle'",fr:"Principal / Principe",wrong:"The principle reason for the failure was lack of funding.",right:"The principal reason for the failure was lack of funding.",rule:"'Principal' and 'principle' are homophones (they sound identical) but have completely different meanings and grammatical functions. PRINCIPAL is an adjective meaning 'main' or 'most important': the principal reason, the principal cause, the principal investigator. It is also a noun for the head of a school. PRINCIPLE is a noun meaning 'a fundamental rule or belief': the principle of equality, a moral principle, the principles of academic integrity. Memory aid: a school princiPAL is your PAL (a person); a PRINCIPLE is a ruLE (ends in -le like rule).",ex:[{w:"One of the main principals of democracy is equality.",r:"One of the main principles of democracy is equality."},{w:"The principle objective of the study was to measure impact.",r:"The principal objective of the study was to measure impact."}]},
  {id:"mi12",title:"Pronoun Reference Ambiguity",fr:"Référence pronominale ambiguë",wrong:"When the professor gave the student his assignment, he was surprised.",right:"When the professor gave the student his assignment, the professor was surprised.",rule:"When a sentence contains more than one possible referent for a pronoun (he, she, they, it, this), the reader cannot know with certainty which noun the pronoun refers to. This ambiguity is called a pronoun reference error or antecedent ambiguity, and it is a serious clarity problem in academic writing. The solution is always to repeat the full noun phrase rather than use a pronoun when there is potential for confusion. Academic writing prioritises precision and clarity above all other stylistic concerns — repetition of a noun is never as bad as ambiguity.",ex:[{w:"The government criticised the researchers but they were right.",r:"The government criticised the researchers but the researchers were right."},{w:"After the company hired the consultant, they improved significantly.",r:"After the company hired the consultant, the company improved significantly."}]},
  {id:"mi13",title:"'Complementary' vs 'Complimentary'",fr:"Complémentaire / Flatteur / Gratuit",wrong:"The study provides complimentary evidence for the theory.",right:"The study provides complementary evidence for the theory.",rule:"'Complementary' (from complement) and 'complimentary' (from compliment) are distinct in both meaning and spelling. COMPLEMENTARY means completing, enhancing, or working together to form a whole: 'complementary research methods', 'complementary approaches', 'complementary colours'. COMPLEMENTARY also refers to complementary medicine (alternative therapies). COMPLIMENTARY means either expressing praise ('complimentary remarks') or given free of charge ('complimentary tickets'). In academic writing, you will almost always want 'complementary' when describing methodologies, theories, or approaches that work together.",ex:[{w:"The two approaches are complimentary — they work well together.",r:"The two approaches are complementary — they work well together."},{w:"The conference provided complimentary refreshments.",r:"The conference provided complimentary refreshments. ✅ (Free refreshments)"}]},
  {id:"mi14",title:"Confusion of 'Which' and 'That'",fr:"Lequel / Que",wrong:"The research, that was conducted over three years, found significant results.",right:"The research, which was conducted over three years, found significant results.",rule:"The choice between 'which' and 'that' in relative clauses depends on whether the clause is DEFINING (identifies which one) or NON-DEFINING (adds extra information). DEFINING clauses use 'that' (or 'which') and have no commas: 'The policy that was introduced in 2010 was effective.' NON-DEFINING clauses use 'which' (never 'that') and are set off by commas: 'The policy, which was introduced in 2010, was effective.' The comma signals the clause is additional information, not essential for identification. Note: 'which' can appear in defining clauses without a comma (British English tolerates this), but 'that' is never used in non-defining clauses.",ex:[{w:"The students, that passed the exam, celebrated.",r:"The students who passed the exam celebrated. (defining)"},{w:"The essay that I submitted yesterday received a high mark. ✅","r":""}]},
  {id:"mi15",title:"Overuse of Passive Voice",fr:"Abus de la voix passive",wrong:"The data was collected, the results were analysed, the conclusions were drawn, and the report was written.",right:"The researchers collected data, analysed the results, drew conclusions, and wrote the report.",rule:"Passive voice has legitimate and important uses in academic writing (when the agent is unknown, unimportant, or when objectivity is required). However, systematically using passive for every sentence creates writing that is evasive, heavy, and difficult to read. Modern academic style actively encourages active voice when the agent is clear and important: 'Smith (2019) found...' is clearer and more direct than 'It was found by Smith (2019)...'. A good balance: use passive when the action matters more than the actor; use active when the actor is clearly identified and important for the argument.",ex:[{w:"It is believed by many researchers that...",r:"Many researchers believe that..."},{w:"The study was conducted in order for results to be obtained.",r:"The researchers conducted the study to obtain results."}]},
  {id:"mi16",title:"'Imply' vs 'Infer'",fr:"Impliquer (sous-entendre) / Inférer",wrong:"From the data, we can imply that poverty rates are falling.",right:"From the data, we can infer that poverty rates are falling.",rule:"The imply/infer distinction reflects the direction of communication. IMPLY is what a speaker or writer does: they suggest something without stating it directly. INFER is what a reader, listener, or analyst does: they reach a conclusion based on evidence or what has been implied. 'The data IMPLY' is incorrect because data cannot communicate intent — data do not imply; they provide evidence from which we INFER conclusions. Correct: 'The data suggest that...' or 'We can infer from the data that...' In academic writing, using 'infer' where 'imply' is meant, or vice versa, signals a misunderstanding of analytical language.",ex:[{w:"The author implies that the government failed. ✅","r":""},{w:"The statistics imply that unemployment is rising.",r:"The statistics suggest / indicate that unemployment is rising. OR We infer from the statistics that unemployment is rising."}]},
  {id:"mi17",title:"'Fewer' vs 'Less'",fr:"Moins (dénombrable) / Moins (indénombrable)",wrong:"There are less universities in rural areas than in cities.",right:"There are fewer universities in rural areas than in cities.",rule:"The fewer/less distinction mirrors the countable/uncountable noun distinction. FEWER is used with countable nouns — things you can count individually: fewer students, fewer universities, fewer participants, fewer studies. LESS is used with uncountable nouns — things measured in quantity but not counted individually: less funding, less time, less research, less information. Universities are countable (one university, two universities) → 'fewer universities'. Funding is uncountable (you cannot say 'one funding, two fundings') → 'less funding'. In informal spoken English, 'less' is used for both, but in formal academic writing, the distinction must be maintained.",ex:[{w:"She has less students in her class this year.",r:"She has fewer students in her class this year."},{w:"We have less resources than before.",r:"We have fewer resources than before. (countable) OR less funding (uncountable)"}]},
  {id:"mi18",title:"Punctuation of 'In addition'",fr:"De plus / En outre",wrong:"In addition the report highlights several policy recommendations.",right:"In addition, the report highlights several policy recommendations.",rule:"Introductory adverbial phrases and conjunctive adverbs placed at the beginning of a sentence are always followed by a comma in formal English. This includes: In addition, Furthermore, Moreover, However, Nevertheless, Consequently, Therefore, As a result, On the other hand, For example, In contrast, By contrast, In conclusion, To summarise. The comma signals a pause and separates the connector from the main clause. Omitting this comma is a punctuation error that, while not always creating ambiguity, marks writing as informal or insufficiently edited. Always proofread specifically for this pattern.",ex:[{w:"Furthermore the evidence supports this conclusion.",r:"Furthermore, the evidence supports this conclusion."},{w:"Moreover access to education remains limited.",r:"Moreover, access to education remains limited."}]},
  {id:"mi19",title:"'Despite' vs 'In spite of' vs 'Although'",fr:"Malgré / Bien que",wrong:"Despite the poverty rates are high, significant progress has been made.",right:"Despite high poverty rates, significant progress has been made. / Although poverty rates are high, significant progress has been made.",rule:"'Despite' and 'in spite of' are prepositions, not conjunctions. Prepositions must be followed by nouns, pronouns, or gerunds — not by complete clauses (subject + verb). 'Despite the poverty rates are high' incorrectly places a clause after a preposition. The fixes: use a noun phrase ('Despite high poverty rates...'), use a gerund ('Despite poverty rates being high...'), use 'the fact that' + clause ('Despite the fact that poverty rates are high...'), or switch to a conjunction ('Although poverty rates are high...'). In academic writing, 'despite' and 'in spite of' are often more elegant than 'although' because they are more compact.",ex:[{w:"Despite the fact she studied hard, she failed.",r:"Despite studying hard, she failed. / Although she studied hard, she failed."},{w:"In spite of it was raining, they continued.",r:"Despite the rain, they continued. / Although it was raining, they continued."}]},
  {id:"mi20",title:"Confusing 'Economic' and 'Economical'",fr:"Économique / Économe",wrong:"The country needs more economical development.",right:"The country needs more economic development.",rule:"'Economic' and 'economical' are related but distinct adjectives. ECONOMIC = relating to the economy, economics, or financial systems: economic growth, economic policy, economic development, economic analysis. ECONOMICAL = efficient, avoiding waste, using resources carefully: an economical car, an economical use of words, a more economical approach. In academic writing, you will almost always need 'economic' when discussing macroeconomic or policy topics. 'Economical' typically appears when describing efficiency or frugality in resource use.",ex:[{w:"The government introduced new economical reforms.",r:"The government introduced new economic reforms."},{w:"This method is more economical — it uses less energy.",r:"This method is more economical — it uses less energy. ✅"}]},
  {id:"mi21",title:"Vague Use of 'This'",fr:"Ce / Cela (référence vague)",wrong:"Deforestation reduces biodiversity. This affects communities. This leads to poverty.",right:"Deforestation reduces biodiversity. This loss of biodiversity affects local communities. Such environmental degradation ultimately leads to poverty.",rule:"Vague pronoun reference — using 'this', 'it', 'that', or 'they' without a clear noun referent — is one of the most common clarity problems in student academic writing. In academic prose, every use of 'this' should ideally be followed by a noun that specifies what 'this' refers to: 'this finding', 'this approach', 'this evidence', 'this failure'. Using 'this' alone (as a pronoun) forces the reader to guess the referent, which slows comprehension and reduces precision. Make a habit of asking: 'This WHAT?' every time you write 'this' and then answer that question explicitly.",ex:[{w:"Education improves income. This is important.",r:"Education improves income. This improvement is particularly important for women."},{w:"The policy failed. This caused problems.",r:"The policy failed. This failure caused serious economic problems."}]},
];

export const QUIZ_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"qi01",questions:[
    {q:"'The research ___ published in three leading journals.' Correct passive:",opts:["was","were","has","had"],ans:0,exp:"'Research' (uncountable) is singular → 'was published'. Passive: was/were + past participle."},
    {q:"'Despite ___ hard, she failed the exam.'",opts:["studying","she studied","to study","studied"],ans:0,exp:"'Despite' + noun/gerund. 'Despite studying' — never 'despite she studied'."},
    {q:"'Economic' vs 'economical': 'The country needs ___ reform.'",opts:["economical","economic","economy","economics"],ans:1,exp:"'Economic' relates to the economy. 'Economical' means efficient/avoiding waste."},
    {q:"'There are ___ universities in rural areas.' (countable)",opts:["less","fewer","lesser","little"],ans:1,exp:"'Fewer' with countable nouns. 'Less' with uncountable nouns."},
    {q:"'It is essential that every student ___ on time.' (subjunctive)",opts:["arrives","arrive","to arrive","arriving"],ans:1,exp:"Subjunctive: It is essential/important/necessary that + base verb (no -s)."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi02",questions:[
    {q:"'According to ___' — which is correct?",opts:["According to me, education is important.","According to the WHO report, cases have risen.","According to my opinion, this is wrong.","According to my view, we should act."],ans:1,exp:"'According to' introduces external sources — not your own opinion. Use 'In my opinion' for personal views."},
    {q:"'Affect' vs 'Effect': 'Climate change ___ all living things.'",opts:["effects","affects","affectes","effective"],ans:1,exp:"'Affect' (verb) = to have an impact on. 'Effect' (noun) = the result or outcome."},
    {q:"'She studied medicine ___ she wanted to help people.'",opts:["whereas","while","because","however"],ans:2,exp:"'Because' = reason. 'Whereas' = contrast. 'She studies medicine because she wants to help' shows reason."},
    {q:"'The report, ___ was published last year, contains useful data.'",opts:["that","which","who","whose"],ans:1,exp:"Non-defining relative clause = 'which' (with commas). 'That' is for defining clauses."},
    {q:"'Sensible' in English means:",opts:["easily affected emotionally","showing good judgment","very intelligent","very sensitive"],ans:1,exp:"English 'sensible' = showing good judgment. 'Sensitive' = easily affected emotionally. False friend with French 'sensible'."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi03",questions:[
    {q:"Correct: 'The committee ___ five experts.'",opts:["is comprised of","comprises","is composing","consist"],ans:1,exp:"'Comprises' (active) = correct. 'Is comprised of' is widely considered incorrect. Use 'comprises' or 'is composed of'."},
    {q:"'However' punctuation: Which is correct?",opts:["The results were good, however more research is needed.","The results were good however more research is needed.","The results were good; however, more research is needed.","The results were good. however, more research is needed."],ans:2,exp:"'However' needs a semicolon before it (or a new sentence) and a comma after it."},
    {q:"'Principal' vs 'Principle': 'The ___ reason for failure was funding.'",opts:["principle","principal","main principle","principally"],ans:1,exp:"'Principal' (adjective) = main. 'Principle' (noun) = a rule or belief."},
    {q:"'___ to the crisis, unemployment rose.' Correct:",opts:["Due to","Because","Due to the fact","Owing"],ans:0,exp:"'Due to' + noun/noun phrase. 'Due to the crisis' ✅. 'Because of the crisis' also correct. Never 'due to + clause'."},
    {q:"'Imply' vs 'Infer': 'The data ___ that inequality is rising.'",opts:["implies","infers","inferres","implys"],ans:0,exp:"The data (source) implies. The reader infers FROM the data. The source implies; the recipient infers."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi04",questions:[
    {q:"Which sentence uses the subjunctive correctly?",opts:["It is essential that she attends.","It is essential that she attend.","It is essential that she attending.","It is essential for she to attend."],ans:1,exp:"Subjunctive: It is essential that + subject + BASE verb (no -s for 3rd person singular)."},
    {q:"'The cost of living has ___ significantly.' Correct:",opts:["raised","risen","rose","arisen"],ans:1,exp:"'Rise-rose-risen' is intransitive (no object). 'Raise-raised-raised' needs an object. Costs rise; you raise prices."},
    {q:"Correct use of 'This' in academic writing:",opts:["Poverty causes problems. This affects everything.","Education improves income. This improvement reduces poverty.","The policy failed. This is bad.","Corruption exists. This is a problem."],ans:1,exp:"'This improvement' — specific noun after 'this' makes the reference clear. Vague 'this' weakens academic writing."},
    {q:"'She failed the exam ___ she had studied hard.'",opts:["despite","although","even","however"],ans:1,exp:"'Although' + clause. 'Despite' + noun/gerund. 'Although she had studied' is correct."},
    {q:"Dangling participle: which is correct?",opts:["Having read the report, the findings were clear.","Having read the report, I found the findings clear.","Reading the report, the findings became obvious.","After reading, the findings are clear."],ans:1,exp:"The participial phrase must refer to the main clause subject: 'Having read the report, I found...' — 'I' is both the one who read and found."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi05",questions:[
    {q:"'Complementary' vs 'Complimentary': 'The two methods are ___ — they enhance each other.'",opts:["complimentary","complementary","completing","completing"],ans:1,exp:"'Complementary' = completing or enhancing. 'Complimentary' = flattering or free."},
    {q:"Passive overuse: Which is better academic style?",opts:["It is believed by researchers that...", "Researchers believe that...","It has been found to be believed...","The belief is held that..."],ans:1,exp:"Active voice ('Researchers believe') is clearer and more direct. Passive is acceptable but shouldn't be overused."},
    {q:"'___ the poverty rate is high, development has occurred.'",opts:["Despite","Although","In spite","Because"],ans:1,exp:"'Although' + clause (subject + verb). 'Despite' + noun/gerund. 'Although the poverty rate is high' ✅."},
    {q:"'Fewer' vs 'Less': 'We have ___ time and ___ resources.'",opts:["less / fewer","fewer / fewer","less / less","fewer / less"],ans:2,exp:"'Time' is uncountable → less time. 'Resources' is countable → fewer resources. Wait — 'less resources' is commonly used but strictly incorrect."},
    {q:"Future perfect: 'By next year, she ___ her research.'",opts:["will finish","will have finished","finishes","would finish"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect: will have + past participle. 'Will have finished' by a future point."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi06",questions:[
    {q:"Misuse of 'however': Which is correct?",opts:["She passed, however she wasn't satisfied.","She passed; however, she wasn't satisfied.","She passed however, she wasn't satisfied.","She passed. however she wasn't satisfied."],ans:1,exp:"Semicolon before 'however', comma after: 'passed; however, she wasn't satisfied'."},
    {q:"'The rising poverty rate ___ thousands of families.' (impact, verb)",opts:["effects","affects","affectes","effective"],ans:1,exp:"'Affect' (verb) = to impact. 'Effect' (noun) = the result."},
    {q:"'Due to' vs 'because': Which is correct?",opts:["Due to she was ill, she missed class.","Because she was ill, she missed class.","Due to that she was ill, she missed class.","Owing to she was ill, she missed class."],ans:1,exp:"'Because' + clause ✅. 'Due to' + noun/noun phrase only."},
    {q:"'Principle' or 'principal'? 'The ___ of equality is fundamental.'",opts:["principal","principle","principles","principally"],ans:1,exp:"'Principle' (noun) = a fundamental rule or belief. 'Principal' (adjective) = main."},
    {q:"Correct relative clause: 'The university, ___ founded in 1964, is the oldest in the region.'",opts:["that was","which was","who was","whose was"],ans:1,exp:"Non-defining relative clause about a thing → 'which was'. With commas. Not 'that'."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi07",questions:[
    {q:"'Imply' vs 'Infer': 'The author ___ that the government was corrupt.'",opts:["infers","implies","is inferring","has inferred"],ans:1,exp:"The author (source) implies. The reader infers from what the author writes."},
    {q:"'Economic' or 'economical'? 'This car is very ___ on fuel.'",opts:["economic","economical","economy","economics"],ans:1,exp:"'Economical' = efficient, not wasteful. 'Economic' relates to the economy."},
    {q:"Subjunctive: 'The committee recommends that the policy ___ reviewed.'",opts:["is","be","was","being"],ans:1,exp:"Subjunctive after recommends/suggests/proposes: that + subject + BASE verb. 'That the policy be reviewed'."},
    {q:"Which avoids vague 'this'?",opts:["Education is vital. This matters.","Education is vital. This importance drives policy.","Education is vital. This is clear.","Education is vital. This shows it."],ans:1,exp:"'This importance' — specific noun after 'this' clarifies the reference. Vague 'this matters' is imprecise."},
    {q:"'___ the challenges, the project succeeded.' (despite/although)",opts:["Although","Despite","Even though","In spite that"],ans:1,exp:"'Despite' + noun: 'Despite the challenges'. 'Although' would need a clause: 'Although the challenges were many'."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi08",questions:[
    {q:"'The percentage of students ___ risen.' Correct:",opts:["have","has","had","were"],ans:1,exp:"'Percentage' is singular → 'has risen'. The percentage has risen."},
    {q:"'She ___ her salary from the company.' (received, passive meaning)",opts:["raised","rose","was raised","had raised"],ans:2,exp:"Passive: 'Her salary was raised by the company.' Active: 'The company raised her salary.'"},
    {q:"'Complementary' vs 'complimentary': 'The hotel offers ___ breakfast.'",opts:["complementary","complimentary","completing","free complement"],ans:1,exp:"'Complimentary' = given free of charge or as a compliment. 'Complementary' = completing/enhancing."},
    {q:"Correct: 'The findings, ___ were unexpected, have been confirmed.'",opts:["that","which","who","whose"],ans:1,exp:"Non-defining clause about findings (thing): 'which were unexpected'. With commas."},
    {q:"'In addition, ___ the government must improve infrastructure.' Correct position of comma?",opts:["In addition the government","In addition, the government","In addition; the government","In addition: the government"],ans:1,exp:"Introductory adverbials followed by comma: 'In addition, Furthermore, However, Moreover' + comma."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi09",questions:[
    {q:"Which correctly uses 'whereas'?",opts:["She studies hard whereas she wants to succeed.","Urban areas are wealthy whereas rural areas remain poor.","She passed whereas she was prepared.","He works hard whereas he earns money."],ans:1,exp:"'Whereas' = contrast between two different things. Urban wealthy vs rural poor — contrast ✅."},
    {q:"Dangling participle: correct sentence?",opts:["After studying all night, the exam was easy.","After studying all night, she found the exam easy.","Having studied all night, the exam passed quickly.","Studied all night, the exam was passed."],ans:1,exp:"'She' studied and she found it easy — subject is consistent. 'The exam' cannot study."},
    {q:"'Imply' or 'infer'? 'From the statistics, we can ___ that growth is slowing.'",opts:["imply","infer","inferring","implied"],ans:1,exp:"We (readers) INFER from the statistics. The statistics IMPLY. Readers infer; sources imply."},
    {q:"'The two theories are ___' (they complete each other)",opts:["complimentary","complementary","competing","completing"],ans:1,exp:"'Complementary' = completing or enhancing each other. 'Complimentary' = flattering or free."},
    {q:"Passive or active? 'The researchers ___ the data.' (active preferred)",opts:["were collected","was collected","collected","have been collected"],ans:2,exp:"Active voice: 'The researchers collected the data' — clearer and more direct than passive."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi10",questions:[
    {q:"'Despite ___ the evidence, he maintained his position.'",opts:["he ignored","ignoring","ignored","to ignore"],ans:1,exp:"'Despite' + gerund: 'Despite ignoring the evidence'. Never 'despite + clause'."},
    {q:"'Principal' vs 'principle': 'The school ___ addressed the students.'",opts:["principle","principal","principally","principled"],ans:1,exp:"'Principal' (noun) = head of a school. 'Principle' = a rule or value."},
    {q:"'There are ___ opportunities for women in leadership.' (countable)",opts:["less","fewer","little","lesser"],ans:1,exp:"'Opportunities' is countable → 'fewer opportunities'. 'Less' is for uncountable nouns."},
    {q:"Which correctly avoids 'very'?",opts:["The results were very very positive.","The results were extremely positive and statistically significant.","The results were very much positive.","The results were so very positive."],ans:1,exp:"Replace 'very' with stronger vocabulary: 'extremely positive and statistically significant'."},
    {q:"'It is vital that the government ___ action immediately.'",opts:["takes","take","taking","to take"],ans:1,exp:"Subjunctive: It is vital/essential/important that + subject + BASE verb. 'Take' (not 'takes')."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi11",questions:[
    {q:"'The policy ___ small businesses.' (negative impact, verb)",opts:["effects","affects","affectes","is effecting"],ans:1,exp:"'Affect' (verb) = to impact. The policy affects businesses."},
    {q:"Correct: 'She is ___ about criticism — she gets upset easily.'",opts:["sensible","sensitive","reasonable","logical"],ans:1,exp:"'Sensitive' = easily affected emotionally. 'Sensible' = showing good judgment."},
    {q:"'The project, ___ was launched in 2020, has succeeded.'",opts:["that","which","who","what"],ans:1,exp:"Non-defining clause about a thing (project): 'which'. With commas."},
    {q:"'___ of all, the study lacked sufficient data.' Correct:",opts:["Most importantly","Most important","More importantly","More important"],ans:0,exp:"'Most importantly' = sentence adverb modifying the whole statement. 'Most importantly' is standard academic English."},
    {q:"Passive: 'By 2030, the policy ___ for ten years.'",opts:["will implement","will have been implemented","implemented","was implementing"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect passive: will have been + past participle. Implemented by a future point."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi12",questions:[
    {q:"Correct use of 'despite':","opts":["Despite the economy grew, poverty persisted.","Despite economic growth, poverty persisted.","Despite that the economy grew, poverty persisted.","Despite the economy has grown, poverty persisted."],ans:1,exp:"'Despite' + noun/noun phrase: 'Despite economic growth'. Never 'despite + clause'."},
    {q:"'According to' — which is acceptable?",opts:["According to my opinion","According to me","According to the World Bank","According to my view"],ans:2,exp:"'According to' + external source (organisation, study, person). Never for your own opinion."},
    {q:"'___ the government invest more in education, literacy rates will improve.' (condition)",opts:["If","Unless","Whereas","Although"],ans:0,exp:"First conditional: If + present simple → will + base verb. Cause and effect relationship."},
    {q:"'The committee is ___ experts from five countries.' Correct:",opts:["comprised of","composing of","composed by","composed of"],ans:3,exp:"'Is composed of' ✅ (passive). 'Comprises' ✅ (active). 'Is comprised of' is considered incorrect by many."},
    {q:"Academic writing: improve this sentence: 'There are less people who have access to healthcare.'",opts:["There are fewer people who have access to healthcare.","There are lesser people who have access to healthcare.","There is less people who access healthcare.","There are little people accessing healthcare."],ans:0,exp:"'People' is countable → 'fewer people'. 'Less' is for uncountable nouns."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi13",questions:[
    {q:"Mixed conditional: 'If she ___ harder, she would be more successful today.'",opts:["studied","had studied","studies","would study"],ans:1,exp:"Mixed conditional: past condition (had studied) + present result (would be). Past action affects present."},
    {q:"'The statistics ___ that unemployment is rising.'",opts:["imply","infer","inferring","implied by"],ans:0,exp:"Statistics (data/source) IMPLY a conclusion. Readers INFER from statistics."},
    {q:"Which sentence has correct pronoun reference?",opts:["The professor and the student disagreed; he was wrong.","The professor and the student disagreed; the professor was wrong.","He disagreed with him about the assignment.","They disagreed and it was about the assignment."],ans:1,exp:"Repeating 'the professor' avoids ambiguity about who 'he' refers to."},
    {q:"'___ of the students passed the exam.' (specific group)",opts:["Most","Most of","The most of","Almost"],ans:1,exp:"'Most of the students' = a specific group. 'Most students' = general. Never 'the most of'."},
    {q:"'Raise' or 'rise'? 'The government ___ the minimum wage.'",opts:["risen","rose","raised","has risen"],ans:2,exp:"'Raise' is transitive: the government RAISED the wage (object). 'Rise' is intransitive: wages RISE (no object)."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi14",questions:[
    {q:"Future perfect: 'By 2030, renewable energy ___ 50% of demand in Africa.'",opts:["will meet","will have met","meets","would meet"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect: will have + past participle. Action completed before a future point (by 2030)."},
    {q:"Cleft sentence: '___ was the lack of resources that caused the project to fail.'",opts:["There","This","It","What"],ans:2,exp:"Cleft: 'It was X that...' — emphasises the subject. 'It was the lack of resources that...'"},
    {q:"'Economic' or 'economical'? 'The government introduced new ___ policies.'",opts:["economical","economic","economy","economics"],ans:1,exp:"'Economic policies' = policies about the economy. 'Economical' = avoiding waste."},
    {q:"'Although' or 'despite'? '___ studying hard, she failed.'",opts:["Although studying hard","Despite studying hard","Although she studied hard","Both b and c are correct"],ans:3,exp:"'Despite studying hard' (preposition + gerund) ✅ and 'Although she studied hard' (conjunction + clause) ✅."},
    {q:"'Vague this': improve: 'The policy failed. This was bad.'",opts:["The policy failed. This failure had serious consequences.","The policy failed. This thing was bad.","The policy failed. This showed it.","The policy failed. This failure it was bad."],ans:0,exp:"'This failure' specifies what 'this' refers to, making the writing clearer and more academic."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi15",questions:[
    {q:"'Sensible' or 'sensitive'? 'That was a ___ decision — it showed good judgment.'",opts:["sensitive","sensible","emotional","sensitive"],ans:1,exp:"'Sensible' = showing good judgment. 'Sensitive' = easily affected by emotions. False friend with French."},
    {q:"Subjunctive or indicative? 'I suggest that she ___ her essay.'",opts:["revises","revised","revise","to revise"],ans:2,exp:"After 'suggest that': subjunctive = base verb. 'I suggest that she revise' (not 'revises')."},
    {q:"'___ poverty remains high, the government must act.' (contrast)",opts:["Despite","Although","In spite","Due to"],ans:1,exp:"'Although' + full clause (subject + verb). 'Despite' would need a noun: 'Despite high poverty'."},
    {q:"Overuse of passive: which is better?",opts:["The data was collected and analysed by the researchers.","The researchers collected and analysed the data.","The data were being collected and were analysed by them.","It was collected and then it was analysed."],ans:1,exp:"Active voice is clearer: 'The researchers collected and analysed'. Less wordy than passive."},
    {q:"'The study ___ of three phases.' Correct:",opts:["is comprised","comprises","is composing","composes of"],ans:1,exp:"'Comprises' (active) = correct. 'The study comprises three phases.' 'Is comprised of' is disputed."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi16",questions:[
    {q:"'There are ___ reasons to be optimistic.' (countable)",opts:["less","fewer","little","lesser"],ans:1,exp:"'Reasons' is countable → 'fewer reasons'. 'Less' is only for uncountable nouns."},
    {q:"Correct 'according to': 'The WHO ___ that mental health is underfunded.'",opts:["According to the WHO, mental health is underfunded.","According to my view from the WHO, it's underfunded.","According to what the WHO says, it according to us is underfunded.","The WHO according to their report is underfunding."],ans:0,exp:"'According to the WHO,' + statement. Clean, academic, correct."},
    {q:"Pronoun reference: clear sentence?",opts:["The minister met the director, and he agreed to the plan.","The minister met the director, and the minister agreed to the plan.","They met and he agreed to it.","The meeting happened and agreement was reached."],ans:1,exp:"Repeating 'the minister' removes ambiguity about who 'he' refers to."},
    {q:"'Affect' vs 'effect': 'The ___ of climate change on agriculture are severe.'",opts:["affects","effects","affection","effective"],ans:1,exp:"'Effects' (noun) = the results or outcomes. 'The effects of climate change...'"},
    {q:"'___ to the drought, crop yields fell.' Correct preposition:",opts:["Due","Because","Although","Despite"],ans:0,exp:"'Due to' + noun: 'Due to the drought'. 'Because' + clause: 'Because the drought was severe'."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi17",questions:[
    {q:"Emphasis with 'do': 'Despite doubts, she ___ complete her degree.'",opts:["does","did","has","had"],ans:1,exp:"'Did' for past emphasis: 'She did complete' = she really completed. Used to stress the reality."},
    {q:"Future perfect passive: 'By next year, the law ___ .'",opts:["will change","will have been changed","is changing","would change"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect passive: will have been + past participle: 'will have been changed'."},
    {q:"'Furthermore ___ the study included a control group.' Correct punctuation:",opts:["Furthermore the study","Furthermore; the study","Furthermore, the study","Furthermore: the study"],ans:2,exp:"Introductory adverbs are followed by a comma: 'Furthermore, Moreover, However, Nevertheless' + comma."},
    {q:"'Most of ___ students passed.' Correct:",opts:["the","a","some","any"],ans:0,exp:"'Most of THE students' — when referring to a specific known group, use 'the'."},
    {q:"'In spite of' vs 'although': '___ the challenges, she persevered.'",opts:["Although the challenges","In spite of the challenges","In spite of she faced challenges","Although the challenges were there"],ans:1,exp:"'In spite of' + noun/gerund: 'In spite of the challenges'. 'Although' needs a full clause."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi18",questions:[
    {q:"Third conditional: 'If they ___ earlier, the crisis could have been averted.'",opts:["act","acted","had acted","would act"],ans:2,exp:"Third conditional: if + past perfect (had acted) → would/could have + past participle."},
    {q:"'The ___ reason for the failure was inadequate funding.'",opts:["principle","principally","principal","principles"],ans:2,exp:"'Principal' (adjective) = main, most important. 'The principal reason' = the main reason."},
    {q:"Nominalisation: academic alternative to 'The government implemented the policy'?",opts:["The government's implementing of the policy","The implementation of the policy by the government","Government implemented","Policy implementing"],ans:1,exp:"'The implementation of the policy' — nominalisation converts verb (implement) to noun (implementation)."},
    {q:"'___ the study was small, its findings are significant.'",opts:["Despite","Although","In spite of","Because"],ans:1,exp:"'Although' + full clause. 'Although the study was small' — subject + verb after although."},
    {q:"Passive with agent: 'The report ___ by three independent reviewers.'",opts:["was verified","verified","has verify","is verifying"],ans:0,exp:"Past passive with agent: 'was verified by'. Subject + was/were + past participle + by + agent."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi19",questions:[
    {q:"'Complementary' or 'complimentary'? 'The reviewer was very ___ about her work.'",opts:["complementary","complimentary","completing","enhancing"],ans:1,exp:"'Complimentary' = flattering, expressing admiration. 'Complementary' = completing/enhancing."},
    {q:"Which uses 'whereas' correctly?",opts:["She works hard whereas she earns little.","She works hard whereas she wants to succeed.","She studied whereas she passed.","She works hard whereas working is important."],ans:0,exp:"'Whereas' = contrast. She works hard (contrast) whereas she earns little. Two opposing facts."},
    {q:"'The government has ___ taxes to fund education.'",opts:["risen","rose","raised","arisen"],ans:2,exp:"'Raise' (transitive): the government raised taxes. Object 'taxes' is needed."},
    {q:"Dangling participle: correct sentence?",opts:["Analysing the data, the conclusion was clear.","Analysing the data, the researchers drew clear conclusions.","Having been analysed, the researchers concluded.","The data analysed, conclusions reaching."],ans:1,exp:"'The researchers' analysed and concluded — subject consistent throughout."},
    {q:"Relative clause: 'The policy ___ the government introduced last year has failed.'",opts:["which","that","who","whose"],ans:1,exp:"Defining relative clause (no commas) identifying WHICH policy: use 'that'. 'Which' can also be used here."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi20",questions:[
    {q:"Mixed conditional: 'If she ___ the scholarship, she would be studying abroad now.'",opts:["received","had received","receives","would receive"],ans:1,exp:"Mixed conditional: past condition (had received) + present result (would be studying). Past event affects present."},
    {q:"Cleft for emphasis: '___ was the colonial legacy that shaped modern education systems.'",opts:["There","This","What","It"],ans:3,exp:"Cleft: 'It was X that...' 'It was the colonial legacy that shaped...' — emphasises the cause."},
    {q:"'In addition ___ the economic benefits, there are social advantages.'",opts:["to","of","about","for"],ans:0,exp:"'In addition to' = as well as. 'In addition to the economic benefits...' — prepositional phrase."},
    {q:"Correct nominalisation: 'analyse' → noun form:",opts:["analysation","analysing","analysis","analysement"],ans:2,exp:"'Analysis' is the noun form of 'analyse'. Analysis → analyses (plural)."},
    {q:"'___ of the recommendations were implemented.' (specific group)",opts:["Most","Most of","The most","Almost most"],ans:1,exp:"'Most of the recommendations' — specific group requires 'most of the'. 'Most recommendations' = general."},
  ]},
  {id:"qi21",questions:[
    {q:"'She ___ complete her degree despite many obstacles.' (emphasis)",opts:["does","did","has","had"],ans:1,exp:"'Did complete' = past emphasis. She really completed it. 'Does complete' would be present emphasis."},
    {q:"'It is imperative that all citizens ___ the right to vote.'",opts:["have","has","having","to have"],ans:0,exp:"Subjunctive: It is imperative that + subject + base verb. 'Have' (base form, not 'has')."},
    {q:"Which correctly avoids overusing 'very'?",opts:["The situation is very very critical.","The situation is critically serious and demands immediate attention.","The situation is very seriously.","The situation is a very critical one."],ans:1,exp:"'Critically serious' and 'demands immediate attention' — specific, academic vocabulary replaces weak 'very'."},
    {q:"'Despite ___ the evidence suggested otherwise, they continued.' Correct?",opts:["despite the fact that","although","in spite of that","due to the fact"],ans:1,exp:"'Although' + clause: 'Although the evidence suggested otherwise'. 'Despite' cannot precede a clause."},
    {q:"'By the time the researchers publish, they ___ the data three times.'",opts:["will analyse","will have analysed","have analysed","analysed"],ans:1,exp:"Future perfect: will have + past participle. Action completed before a future point."},
  ]},
];

export const PEEL_INTERMEDIATE = [
  {id:"pi01",theme:"Education",title:"Decolonising the Curriculum",prompt:"African universities should replace European-centred curricula with content that reflects African history, culture, and knowledge systems.",guidance:{point:"Take a clear position on curriculum reform.",explanation:"Explain why the current curriculum is problematic and what change would achieve.",evidence:"Use evidence from research or educational theory.",link:"Connect to the broader context of African development and identity."},vocab:["decolonise","curriculum","identity","knowledge systems","heritage","marginalise","Eurocentric","reform"],sources:[{name:"Achebe (1977)",fact:"In 'An Image of Africa', Achebe argued that European literature systematically dehumanised Africans, and that education systems that centre European knowledge perpetuate this harm."},{name:"UNESCO (2019)",fact:"Studies in 12 African countries found that students who learned about African history and culture in school showed significantly higher academic motivation."}],example:{point:"African universities must urgently reform their curricula to centre African knowledge systems, as continuing to prioritise European content marginalises African students in their own educational institutions.",explanation:"When students study primarily European history, literature, and philosophy, they implicitly learn that African knowledge and experience are of secondary importance. This creates a form of cultural alienation that undermines academic confidence and engagement, particularly among students from rural communities where African traditions remain strong. Furthermore, African-centred knowledge — from indigenous agricultural systems to African philosophy — has enormous practical and intellectual value that is currently being lost.",evidence:"Achebe (1977) demonstrated in 'An Image of Africa' that European educational content has historically dehumanised Africans, while a UNESCO study (2019) found that students learning African history showed significantly higher academic motivation.",link:"Decolonising the curriculum is therefore not merely a cultural statement but a practical educational strategy that would produce more engaged, confident, and ultimately more effective African graduates."}},
  {id:"pi02",theme:"Technology",title:"Artificial Intelligence and African Jobs",prompt:"Artificial intelligence poses a greater threat than opportunity to African workers and economies.",guidance:{point:"Agree or disagree with a nuanced position.",explanation:"Explain the specific mechanisms by which AI threatens or benefits African economies.",evidence:"Use specific data about AI's impact on employment or productivity.",link:"Connect to Africa's broader development trajectory."},vocab:["artificial intelligence","automation","employment","disruption","productivity","leapfrog","inequality","digital divide"],sources:[{name:"World Economic Forum (2022)",fact:"AI automation is projected to displace 85 million jobs globally by 2025 while creating 97 million new ones, but the new jobs require significantly higher digital skills."},{name:"McKinsey (2022)",fact:"African countries could add $1.5 trillion to their combined GDP by 2030 through AI adoption, primarily through productivity gains in agriculture and healthcare."}],example:{point:"While AI presents real risks for African workers, the net effect is more likely to be opportunity than threat, provided African governments and institutions invest strategically in digital skills and infrastructure.",explanation:"The pessimistic view focuses on AI's capacity to automate routine tasks, displacing workers in manufacturing and services. This concern is legitimate, particularly for Africa's large informal sector. However, AI also creates opportunities that are uniquely suited to Africa's context: agricultural AI can transform smallholder farming; AI diagnostic tools can address the shortage of doctors; and AI-powered platforms can connect African businesses to global markets.",evidence:"The World Economic Forum (2022) projects that AI will create 97 million new jobs globally while displacing 85 million, but McKinsey (2022) estimates Africa could gain $1.5 trillion in GDP through strategic AI adoption.",link:"Whether AI becomes threat or opportunity for Africa depends not on the technology itself but on whether African governments make the necessary investments in education, infrastructure, and economic policy to enable their populations to participate fully in the AI economy."}},
  {id:"pi03",theme:"Environment",title:"Climate Justice",prompt:"Wealthy nations have a moral obligation to pay reparations to African countries for the climate damage they have caused.",guidance:{point:"Argue clearly for or against climate reparations.",explanation:"Develop the moral, historical, and practical arguments.",evidence:"Use data about emissions, climate damage, or financial flows.",link:"Connect to international justice and African development."},vocab:["reparations","emissions","justice","responsibility","vulnerability","compensation","obligation","adaptation"],sources:[{name:"IPCC (2022)",fact:"Africa contributes less than 4% of global greenhouse gas emissions yet faces the most severe consequences of climate change, including a projected 4°C temperature increase by 2100."},{name:"Oxfam (2022)",fact:"Rich countries have provided only $23 billion of the $100 billion annually promised in climate finance to developing countries since 2009."}],example:{point:"Wealthy nations do indeed bear a profound moral obligation to compensate African countries for climate damage, given that Africa suffers disproportionately from a crisis it did not create.",explanation:"The logic of climate reparations rests on the well-established principle that those responsible for harm have an obligation to compensate those who suffer from it. The countries that industrialised earliest and emitted the most carbon dioxide over the past 200 years are overwhelmingly wealthy Western nations, while the countries experiencing the most severe consequences — declining agricultural yields, extreme weather events, rising sea levels — are disproportionately in Africa.",evidence:"The IPCC (2022) found that Africa contributes less than 4% of global emissions yet faces the most severe climate consequences, while Oxfam (2022) revealed that rich countries have delivered only $23 billion of the $100 billion annually promised in climate finance.",link:"Acknowledging this obligation and translating it into meaningful financial transfers is not merely a matter of justice — it is a prerequisite for the global cooperation needed to address a climate crisis that threatens all of humanity."}},
  {id:"pi04",theme:"Society",title:"Gender and Traditional Values",prompt:"Traditional cultural values in Africa are an obstacle to gender equality.",guidance:{point:"Agree, disagree, or argue a nuanced position.",explanation:"Examine the relationship between tradition and gender equality critically.",evidence:"Use evidence about gender equality indicators in Africa.",link:"Connect to the broader debate about culture and development."},vocab:["tradition","gender equality","patriarchy","empowerment","stereotype","agency","culture","modernisation"],sources:[{name:"World Bank (2022)",fact:"Countries in sub-Saharan Africa with stronger gender equality indices have 40% higher rates of economic growth than those with the lowest gender equality scores."},{name:"Oyewùmí (1997)",fact:"In her book 'The Invention of Women', African scholar Oyèrónkẹ Oyewùmí argued that pre-colonial Yoruba society had no gender hierarchy — gender inequality was introduced by colonial Christianity and Western education."}],example:{point:"The relationship between African traditional values and gender equality is far more complex than a simple opposition: while some traditional practices do constrain women, others have been misrepresented as inherently patriarchal when the patriarchy was in fact a colonial imposition.",explanation:"It would be intellectually dishonest to pretend that practices like early marriage, female genital mutilation, or inheritance laws that exclude women do not exist in some African communities — they do, and they cause real harm. However, attributing these solely to 'African tradition' ignores the historical evidence that many pre-colonial African societies had far more equitable gender relations, and that current inequalities were often intensified by colonial policies.",evidence:"Scholar Oyèrónkẹ Oyewùmí (1997) demonstrated that pre-colonial Yoruba society had no gender hierarchy, while the World Bank (2022) found that countries with higher gender equality indices have 40% higher economic growth rates.",link:"Rather than rejecting African culture as inherently patriarchal, a more productive approach distinguishes between traditions that harm women and those that empower them, using African intellectual traditions themselves to advance the cause of gender justice."}},
  {id:"pi05",theme:"Politics",title:"Electoral Democracy vs Developmental State",prompt:"Africa needs strong developmental states more than it needs multi-party electoral democracy.",guidance:{point:"Take a position in this debate.",explanation:"Explain the arguments for and against prioritising development over democracy.",evidence:"Use historical examples or data from African countries.",link:"Connect to Africa's future development needs."},vocab:["developmental state","democracy","accountability","authoritarian","governance","elections","growth","institutions"],sources:[{name:"Mo Ibrahim Foundation (2022)",fact:"The 2022 Ibrahim Index of African Governance found that countries with the highest democracy scores also had the highest human development indicators."},{name:"World Bank Research (2019)",fact:"Over the past 30 years, African democracies have grown on average 1.5% faster annually than non-democracies, with greater resilience to economic shocks."}],example:{point:"The framing of democracy against development is a false choice: the evidence consistently shows that democratic governance and sustainable development reinforce rather than contradict each other.",explanation:"Proponents of developmental authoritarianism typically point to East Asian examples — South Korea, Singapore — as evidence that strong states can drive rapid development without democratic accountability. However, this argument ignores the historical specificity of these cases and the fact that African authoritarian regimes have generally failed to deliver comparable results while producing significant human rights abuses and institutional decay.",evidence:"The Mo Ibrahim Foundation (2022) found that African countries with the highest democracy scores also have the best human development indicators, while World Bank research (2019) shows African democracies growing 1.5% faster annually than non-democracies.",link:"Rather than choosing between democracy and development, African leaders and citizens should focus on building the quality of both: stronger democratic institutions that are genuinely responsive to citizens' needs are the most reliable foundation for the kind of sustainable development Africa requires."}},
  {id:"pi06",theme:"Economy",title:"Brain Drain and African Development",prompt:"African countries should do more to prevent the emigration of educated professionals.",guidance:{point:"Agree or disagree with a clear argument.",explanation:"Examine the causes and effects of brain drain and possible solutions.",evidence:"Use data about brain drain and its economic effects.",link:"Connect to African development and the global talent economy."},vocab:["brain drain","emigration","talent","diaspora","remittances","capacity","incentive","retain"],sources:[{name:"African Union (2021)",fact:"Africa loses an estimated 70,000 skilled professionals annually to emigration, costing the continent approximately $4 billion in lost human capital investment."},{name:"World Bank (2022)",fact:"African diaspora remittances totalled $95 billion in 2021 — more than three times Africa's official development aid receipts."}],example:{point:"Rather than attempting to prevent brain drain through restriction, African governments should focus on creating the conditions that make talented professionals want to remain, while building strategic connections with their diasporas.",explanation:"The instinct to prevent emigration is understandable: Africa loses billions in human capital investment when trained doctors, engineers, and academics leave for higher salaries and better working conditions abroad. However, attempts to prevent emigration through restriction are likely to fail and may be unjust — people have the right to move freely. A more effective approach creates competitive salaries, good working environments, and clear career paths that make remaining in Africa an attractive choice.",evidence:"The African Union (2021) estimates that Africa loses 70,000 skilled professionals annually worth $4 billion, but the World Bank (2022) found that diaspora remittances totalled $95 billion in 2021 — suggesting the diaspora relationship can be a net asset if managed well.",link:"A comprehensive brain drain strategy must therefore combine domestic reforms to retain talent with diaspora engagement policies that convert the skills and resources of Africans abroad into investment in the continent's development."}},
  {id:"pi07",theme:"Health",title:"Universal Healthcare",prompt:"Universal healthcare coverage should be the top health priority for African governments.",guidance:{point:"Agree and argue for universal healthcare.",explanation:"Explain what universal healthcare means and why it is prioritised.",evidence:"Use data about healthcare access and outcomes in Africa.",link:"Connect to development and human rights."},vocab:["universal healthcare","access","equity","primary healthcare","out-of-pocket","investment","insurance","coverage"],sources:[{name:"WHO (2022)",fact:"In sub-Saharan Africa, 65% of healthcare spending is out-of-pocket, pushing 11 million people into poverty annually."},{name:"The Lancet (2021)",fact:"African countries that have implemented universal health coverage schemes have seen a 35% reduction in catastrophic health expenditure among the poorest quintile."}],example:{point:"Universal healthcare coverage should indeed be the highest health priority for African governments because it simultaneously addresses poverty, productivity, and human dignity.",explanation:"When families must pay for healthcare directly, the consequences are severe: sick people delay treatment until illnesses become acute and expensive; families sell assets or take on debt to pay for care; and the poorest consistently receive the least care despite having the greatest needs. Universal coverage breaks this cycle by pooling risk across the population.",evidence:"The WHO (2022) found that 65% of African healthcare spending is out-of-pocket, pushing 11 million people into poverty annually, while The Lancet (2021) showed that countries implementing universal coverage saw a 35% reduction in catastrophic health expenditure.",link:"Universal healthcare is not merely a health intervention — it is a poverty reduction strategy, an economic investment, and a fulfilment of the most fundamental human rights obligations that African governments have to their citizens."}},
  {id:"pi08",theme:"Côte d'Ivoire",title:"Economic Diversification",prompt:"Côte d'Ivoire's dependence on cocoa and coffee exports is a dangerous vulnerability that must be urgently addressed.",guidance:{point:"Agree and argue for economic diversification.",explanation:"Explain the risks of commodity dependence and the benefits of diversification.",evidence:"Use data about Côte d'Ivoire's economy and commodity prices.",link:"Connect to long-term development sustainability."},vocab:["diversification","commodity","vulnerability","dependence","value added","manufacturing","export","sustainable"],sources:[{name:"World Bank (2022)",fact:"Côte d'Ivoire earns approximately 40% of its export revenues from cocoa, making it highly vulnerable to price fluctuations — cocoa prices fell by 35% between 2016 and 2019."},{name:"AfDB (2021)",fact:"African countries that successfully diversified their economies between 2000 and 2020 achieved on average 2.3% higher annual growth rates than commodity-dependent economies."}],example:{point:"Côte d'Ivoire's heavy dependence on cocoa and coffee does indeed represent a serious structural vulnerability that threatens the sustainability of the country's impressive recent economic growth.",explanation:"A national economy so heavily reliant on two commodities is exposed to price volatility it cannot control. When international cocoa prices fall — as they did by 35% between 2016 and 2019 — government revenues, farmer incomes, and economic growth all suffer dramatically. Diversification into manufacturing, services, and processed goods would provide more stable and higher-value income streams.",evidence:"The World Bank (2022) notes that 40% of Côte d'Ivoire's export revenues come from cocoa alone, making it highly exposed to price shocks, while the AfDB (2021) found that diversified African economies grew 2.3% faster annually than commodity-dependent ones.",link:"Diversifying Côte d'Ivoire's economy is therefore not a question of abandoning cocoa and coffee — which will remain important — but of building the manufacturing, technology, and service sectors that will provide stable prosperity for future generations."}},
  {id:"pi09",theme:"Culture",title:"Social Media and African Identity",prompt:"Social media platforms designed in the West are undermining African cultural identity and values.",guidance:{point:"Agree, disagree, or argue a nuanced position.",explanation:"Examine how social media interacts with African culture.",evidence:"Use evidence about social media use and cultural change.",link:"Connect to cultural sovereignty and African identity."},vocab:["social media","identity","cultural imperialism","values","authenticity","influence","platform","narrative"],sources:[{name:"Statista (2023)",fact:"Over 400 million Africans use social media, with WhatsApp, Facebook, and TikTok dominating — all platforms owned by US companies."},{name:"Pew Research (2022)",fact:"67% of young Africans surveyed said social media helped them connect with their cultural heritage and community."}],example:{point:"The relationship between social media and African cultural identity is more complex than simple cultural imperialism: these platforms simultaneously threaten and strengthen aspects of African culture.",explanation:"There are genuine concerns: algorithm-driven content from Western platforms disproportionately promotes Western aesthetic standards, entertainment styles, and values. Young Africans spending hours daily on TikTok and Instagram consume enormous amounts of content that normalises Western lifestyles while African content creators struggle for visibility. This does create real cultural pressure.",evidence:"Statista (2023) notes that over 400 million Africans use platforms all owned by US companies, yet Pew Research (2022) found that 67% of young Africans said social media helped them connect with their cultural heritage.",link:"The solution is not to reject social media but to demand platforms that give African voices, languages, and cultures equal algorithmic visibility, while developing African-owned platforms that serve African values and communities."}},
  {id:"pi10",theme:"Environment",title:"Renewable Energy Transition",prompt:"Africa should prioritise renewable energy development over fossil fuel extraction to fuel its economic growth.",guidance:{point:"Agree with the renewable priority argument.",explanation:"Explain why renewables serve Africa's long-term interests better than fossil fuels.",evidence:"Use data about renewable energy costs and potential.",link:"Connect to climate commitments and development."},vocab:["renewable energy","fossil fuels","transition","solar","investment","infrastructure","sustainable","leapfrog"],sources:[{name:"IRENA (2023)",fact:"The cost of solar electricity in Africa has fallen 90% over the past decade, making it now cheaper than new coal or gas in most African markets."},{name:"IEA (2022)",fact:"If Africa develops its full renewable potential, it could generate 100 times its current electricity demand and become a major clean energy exporter."}],example:{point:"Africa should prioritise renewable energy development because the continent has both a unique opportunity and a strong economic incentive to leapfrog fossil fuel dependence entirely.",explanation:"Africa's energy situation differs fundamentally from Europe or North America, where existing fossil fuel infrastructure must be costly replaced. Most of Africa's energy infrastructure remains to be built — and building it around renewables from the start makes both economic and environmental sense. Solar, wind, and hydroelectric resources are abundant, increasingly cheap, and compatible with the distributed energy systems that suit Africa's geography.",evidence:"IRENA (2023) reports that solar costs in Africa have fallen 90% in a decade, making it cheaper than coal or gas, while the IEA (2022) estimates Africa could generate 100 times its current electricity demand from renewables.",link:"By choosing renewables over fossil fuels, Africa would simultaneously address energy poverty, create clean industries, attract international climate investment, and position itself as a global leader in the energy transition."}},
  {id:"pi11",theme:"Society",title:"Immigration Policy in Africa",prompt:"African countries should adopt open borders policies to facilitate the free movement of people across the continent.",guidance:{point:"Agree or disagree with a clear argument.",explanation:"Examine the economic and social effects of open borders in Africa.",evidence:"Use evidence from African free movement initiatives.",link:"Connect to African integration and development."},vocab:["open borders","migration","free movement","integration","AfCFTA","labour market","sovereignty","mobility"],sources:[{name:"African Union (2022)",fact:"The African Continental Free Trade Area could add $450 billion to African GDP by 2035, but analysts say this potential is significantly limited without accompanying free movement of people."},{name:"World Bank (2021)",fact:"Intra-African migrants earn on average 130% more than they would in their country of origin, and send significant remittances home."}],example:{point:"African countries should progressively adopt free movement policies within the continent because labour mobility is essential for making the African Continental Free Trade Area work and for achieving shared prosperity.",explanation:"Trade integration without labour mobility is economically incomplete. If goods can cross borders freely but workers cannot follow economic opportunities, the benefits of trade integration are severely limited. Workers in Côte d'Ivoire may have skills urgently needed in Ghana, or Senegalese entrepreneurs may see opportunities in Nigeria, but without legal channels for movement, these productive matches cannot occur.",evidence:"The World Bank (2021) found that intra-African migrants earn 130% more than they would at home, while the African Union (2022) warned that AfCFTA's $450 billion potential is limited without free movement.",link:"Progressive implementation of free movement across Africa — starting within existing regional economic communities and expanding gradually — would therefore accelerate the economic integration that African countries have correctly identified as essential for development."}},
  {id:"pi12",theme:"Education",title:"Technical and Vocational Education",prompt:"African education systems should invest more in technical and vocational training and less in traditional university education.",guidance:{point:"Agree with a nuanced argument.",explanation:"Explain the mismatch between university education and labour market needs.",evidence:"Use data about youth unemployment and skills gaps.",link:"Connect to the practical development needs of African economies."},vocab:["vocational","technical","skills","labour market","employability","curriculum","practical","training"],sources:[{name:"African Development Bank (2022)",fact:"Over 60% of African university graduates report difficulties finding employment relevant to their degrees within two years of graduation."},{name:"ILO (2021)",fact:"Technical and vocational training graduates in Africa have a 40% higher employment rate than university graduates in the first five years after graduation."}],example:{point:"African education systems should significantly expand technical and vocational training because a fundamental mismatch between graduate skills and labour market needs is wasting both individual potential and public resources.",explanation:"Africa's economies need builders, electricians, mechanics, nurses, coders, and agricultural technicians — and yet the dominant model produces arts and social science graduates for jobs that do not exist in sufficient numbers. Technical and vocational education, when well-designed and properly resourced, produces graduates with directly applicable skills that employers actively seek.",evidence:"The African Development Bank (2022) found that over 60% of African university graduates struggle to find relevant employment, while the ILO (2021) reported that vocational graduates have a 40% higher employment rate than university graduates.",link:"Rebalancing African education towards technical and vocational training would not diminish the value of education — it would enhance its relevance, its economic returns, and its contribution to the development that African societies urgently need."}},
  {id:"pi13",theme:"Politics",title:"Judicial Independence",prompt:"Independent judiciaries are the most important institution for Africa's democratic development.",guidance:{point:"Agree and argue for judicial independence.",explanation:"Explain why judicial independence is foundational for democracy and development.",evidence:"Use examples or data about judicial independence and governance.",link:"Connect to Africa's democratic trajectory."},vocab:["judiciary","independence","rule of law","accountability","democracy","corruption","constitution","institution"],sources:[{name:"Transparency International (2022)",fact:"African countries with highly rated judicial independence score on average 35 points higher on corruption perception indices than those with weak judicial systems."},{name:"Mo Ibrahim Foundation (2022)",fact:"Countries with independent judiciaries in Africa show 25% higher rates of foreign direct investment than comparable countries without judicial independence."}],example:{point:"Independent judiciaries are indeed the cornerstone of democratic governance in Africa because without judicial independence, all other democratic institutions are ultimately hollow.",explanation:"Elections produce legitimate governments, but elections alone cannot protect citizens from those governments. Free press can expose corruption, but exposure without consequences is meaningless. It is only an independent judiciary — capable of ruling against the government, enforcing constitutional limits on power, and protecting individual rights — that gives substance to democratic governance.",evidence:"Transparency International (2022) found that African countries with strong judicial independence score 35 points higher on corruption indices, while the Mo Ibrahim Foundation (2022) reports 25% higher foreign investment in countries with independent courts.",link:"Investing in the independence, capacity, and integrity of African judiciaries is therefore not a technical legal exercise but one of the most consequential investments in democratic development and economic prosperity that African societies can make."}},
  {id:"pi14",theme:"Health",title:"Traditional Medicine Integration",prompt:"African healthcare systems should formally integrate traditional medicine alongside modern biomedical practices.",guidance:{point:"Agree with a nuanced position.",explanation:"Explain the potential benefits and necessary safeguards of integration.",evidence:"Use evidence about traditional medicine's effectiveness.",link:"Connect to African healthcare capacity and cultural context."},vocab:["traditional medicine","integrate","biomedical","evidence-based","regulation","efficacy","cultural","complementary"],sources:[{name:"WHO Africa (2022)",fact:"Over 80% of Africans use traditional medicine as their primary healthcare, yet only 40% of African countries have formal policies regulating traditional healers."},{name:"The Lancet (2020)",fact:"A study of 15 African countries found that patients who received integrated traditional-biomedical care reported 28% higher satisfaction and showed comparable clinical outcomes to those receiving only biomedical care."}],example:{point:"Formally integrating traditional medicine into African healthcare systems would be both practically sensible and culturally appropriate, provided integration is guided by evidence and proper regulation.",explanation:"The reality of African healthcare is that most people consult traditional healers before biomedical practitioners — not because they prefer to avoid hospitals, but because healers are closer, more affordable, speak local languages, and understand cultural contexts. Ignoring this reality in health policy simply ensures that most Africans never benefit from the best of either system.",evidence:"The WHO Africa (2022) reports that over 80% of Africans use traditional medicine primarily, while research published in The Lancet (2020) found that integrated care produced comparable clinical outcomes and significantly higher patient satisfaction.",link:"Formal integration, with proper training, regulation, and evidence-based standards, would extend healthcare coverage dramatically, reduce costs, and create a genuinely African healthcare model that serves African communities rather than simply imitating Western systems."}},
  {id:"pi15",theme:"Economy",title:"Chinese Investment in Africa",prompt:"Chinese investment in Africa is more beneficial than harmful for African development.",guidance:{point:"Argue a nuanced position on Chinese investment.",explanation:"Examine both the benefits and concerns about Chinese investment in Africa.",evidence:"Use data about Chinese investment and its effects.",link:"Connect to African agency and development strategy."},vocab:["investment","infrastructure","debt","sovereignty","partnership","conditionality","trade","development"],sources:[{name:"SAIS-CARI (2022)",fact:"China invested over $48 billion in African infrastructure between 2014 and 2021, making it the continent's largest bilateral infrastructure financier."},{name:"Debt Justice (2022)",fact:"21 African countries have public debt to China exceeding 10% of their GDP, with some critics warning of a 'debt trap' limiting sovereign economic policy choices."}],example:{point:"Chinese investment in Africa is on balance more beneficial than harmful, but the terms and governance of this investment require critical scrutiny and stronger African negotiating positions.",explanation:"China has financed roads, railways, ports, and power plants across Africa at a scale that Western donors and multilateral institutions have been unable or unwilling to match. This infrastructure is genuinely valuable for development. However, concerns about loan terms that transfer risk to African governments, contract terms that favour Chinese companies and workers, and potential 'debt trap' dynamics are legitimate and cannot be dismissed.",evidence:"SAIS-CARI (2022) documents $48 billion in Chinese infrastructure investment since 2014, while Debt Justice (2022) notes that 21 African countries have Chinese debt exceeding 10% of GDP.",link:"Africa should neither reject nor uncritically accept Chinese investment, but negotiate from a position of informed self-interest — welcoming infrastructure financing while insisting on terms that genuinely serve African development, employment, and sovereignty."}},
  {id:"pi16",theme:"Culture",title:"African Languages in Higher Education",prompt:"African universities should use African languages as primary languages of instruction.",guidance:{point:"Argue for or against African languages in higher education.",explanation:"Examine the practical, cognitive, and cultural dimensions of this question.",evidence:"Use research on language and learning in higher education.",link:"Connect to African development and global competitiveness."},vocab:["mother tongue","instruction","competitiveness","identity","access","bilingual","academic","policy"],sources:[{name:"UNESCO (2022)",fact:"Students taught in their mother tongue at university level show 25% higher comprehension and academic performance than those taught in a second language."},{name:"DAAD (2021)",fact:"Only 1% of scientific research published from Africa uses African languages, and fewer than 5% of African professionals report being able to work effectively in an African language in their field."}],example:{point:"African universities should transition to African languages as primary languages of instruction because the current dependence on colonial languages creates unnecessary barriers to learning while perpetuating colonial power structures.",explanation:"The cognitive case is clear: students understand and retain more when taught in the language they think in. The practical case for African languages is also growing: as African economies mature, the demand for professional communication in Zulu, Swahili, Hausa, and other African languages is increasing. And the cultural case is undeniable — universities that teach exclusively in French or English implicitly message that African languages are not vehicles for serious intellectual work.",evidence:"UNESCO (2022) found that students taught in their mother tongue at university show 25% higher comprehension, while DAAD (2021) reports that only 1% of African research uses African languages, suggesting how much intellectual potential is being lost.",link:"Transitioning to African languages in higher education would require significant investment in academic terminology development and faculty training, but would ultimately produce graduates who are both intellectually stronger and more deeply connected to the communities they will serve."}},
  {id:"pi17",theme:"Society",title:"Social Media Regulation",prompt:"African governments should regulate social media platforms to combat misinformation and hate speech.",guidance:{point:"Agree or disagree with clear arguments.",explanation:"Examine the balance between free speech and the harms of unregulated social media.",evidence:"Use evidence about social media's effects on African societies.",link:"Connect to democracy, rights, and governance."},vocab:["regulation","misinformation","hate speech","censorship","democracy","platform","accountability","freedom"],sources:[{name:"Freedom House (2022)",fact:"In 12 of 25 African countries studied, governments used internet shutdowns or social media restrictions during elections in 2021-22, often citing misinformation."},{name:"Reuters Institute (2022)",fact:"In sub-Saharan Africa, social media is the primary news source for 70% of people under 30, making platform content moderation critically important for information quality."}],example:{point:"African governments have a legitimate interest in regulating social media to combat genuine harms, but this regulation must be limited, transparent, and independently overseen to prevent it from becoming a tool of political censorship.",explanation:"The case for regulation is real: social media platforms have been weaponised for ethnic incitement, election interference, and the spread of dangerous medical misinformation across Africa. The case against government regulation is equally real: many African governments have used 'misinformation' as a pretext for silencing legitimate political opposition, shutting down internet access during elections, and targeting journalists.",evidence:"Freedom House (2022) found that 12 of 25 African governments restricted social media during elections, while Reuters Institute (2022) notes that 70% of young Africans get news from social media.",link:"The solution is not to choose between unregulated harm and government censorship, but to develop independent, multi-stakeholder regulatory frameworks that hold platforms accountable for genuine harms while protecting freedom of expression from governmental abuse."}},
  {id:"pi18",theme:"Environment",title:"Sustainable Agriculture",prompt:"Transitioning African agriculture to sustainable practices is the most urgent environmental challenge the continent faces.",guidance:{point:"Agree and argue for sustainable agricultural transition.",explanation:"Explain the links between agriculture, environment, and food security.",evidence:"Use data about African agricultural practices and environmental impacts.",link:"Connect to climate, food security, and development."},vocab:["sustainable","agriculture","deforestation","soil","food security","smallholder","biodiversity","agroecology"],sources:[{name:"FAO (2022)",fact:"Agriculture accounts for approximately 70% of deforestation in Africa and 20% of the continent's greenhouse gas emissions."},{name:"CGIAR (2021)",fact:"Agroecological farming practices can increase yields by 80% in sub-Saharan Africa while reducing input costs by 30% and improving soil health."}],example:{point:"Transitioning to sustainable agricultural practices is indeed the most urgent environmental priority for Africa, as current farming methods simultaneously threaten food security, accelerate climate change, and destroy the natural systems that agriculture depends upon.",explanation:"The paradox of African agriculture is that practices aimed at producing more food in the short term are destroying the soil, water, and biodiversity that will be needed to produce food in the future. Slash-and-burn clearing of forests, overgrazing, and excessive agrochemical use degrade land productivity over time, forcing farmers to clear more forest in a destructive cycle.",evidence:"The FAO (2022) reports that agriculture drives 70% of African deforestation, while CGIAR (2021) found that agroecological practices can increase yields 80% while reducing costs 30%.",link:"Transitioning African agriculture to sustainable practices would simultaneously address food security, climate change, and biodiversity loss — making it the single intervention with the greatest potential to benefit both current and future generations of Africans."}},
  {id:"pi19",theme:"Politics",title:"Youth in Politics",prompt:"African political systems need mandatory youth quotas to ensure adequate representation of young people.",guidance:{point:"Agree or disagree with youth quotas.",explanation:"Examine the arguments for and against mandatory representation.",evidence:"Use data about youth political representation.",link:"Connect to democracy and generational equity."},vocab:["quota","representation","youth","parliament","democracy","inclusion","policy","governance"],sources:[{name:"UN (2021)",fact:"Despite young people (under 35) comprising 60% of Africa's population, only 4% of African MPs are under 35 years old."},{name:"Inter-Parliamentary Union (2022)",fact:"Countries with mandatory gender quotas in parliaments have on average 34% female representation, compared to 16% in countries without quotas."}],example:{point:"Mandatory youth quotas are a necessary corrective to the systematic under-representation of young Africans in political decision-making, but they must be accompanied by meaningful capacity support.",explanation:"When 60% of a population is almost entirely absent from the institution that makes decisions about their future, something has gone wrong with democracy. Young people in Africa face the most acute consequences of decisions about climate change, education, employment, and technology, yet they have almost no voice in making those decisions. Voluntary approaches have clearly failed.",evidence:"The UN (2021) found that young people are 60% of Africa's population but just 4% of MPs, while the Inter-Parliamentary Union (2022) shows that gender quota countries achieve twice the representation of non-quota countries.",link:"Mandatory youth quotas, combined with training and mentorship, would inject both demographic legitimacy and fresh perspectives into African political systems that currently risk becoming gerontocracies increasingly disconnected from the majority of their populations."}},
  {id:"pi20",theme:"Economy",title:"Remittances and Development",prompt:"African diaspora remittances are more effective than foreign aid for African development.",guidance:{point:"Argue this position with evidence.",explanation:"Compare remittances and foreign aid in terms of scale, efficiency, and impact.",evidence:"Use data about remittances and aid flows.",link:"Connect to diaspora engagement and development financing."},vocab:["remittances","diaspora","foreign aid","development finance","efficiency","conditionality","investment","community"],sources:[{name:"World Bank (2022)",fact:"African diaspora remittances reached $95 billion in 2022 — more than three times the $30 billion in official development assistance received by Africa."},{name:"UN DESA (2021)",fact:"Remittances go directly to families and communities, with studies showing 70% are spent on basic needs — food, education, healthcare — while 30% are invested in small businesses."}],example:{point:"African diaspora remittances are indeed more effective than traditional foreign aid for development precisely because they are larger in volume, more direct in delivery, and better targeted to genuine community needs.",explanation:"The comparison between remittances and aid is striking at every level. Remittances are three times larger in volume. They bypass government bureaucracies and reach families directly. They carry no political conditionality. They require no complex project design or evaluation frameworks. And unlike aid, which is determined by donor priorities, remittances reflect the intimate knowledge that diaspora members have of their own families' and communities' actual needs.",evidence:"The World Bank (2022) documents $95 billion in African remittances against $30 billion in aid, while UN DESA (2021) shows 70% of remittances directly fund basic needs and 30% go into small business investment.",link:"Rather than debating whether Africa needs more foreign aid, development policy should focus on reducing the cost of sending remittances, creating investment vehicles that allow diaspora savings to fund productive enterprise, and building the diaspora partnerships that can channel Africa's most committed development supporters most effectively."}},
  {id:"pi21",theme:"Culture",title:"Heritage and Modernity",prompt:"African societies do not have to choose between preserving their cultural heritage and embracing modernity — the two are compatible.",guidance:{point:"Argue that heritage and modernity are compatible.",explanation:"Challenge the false dichotomy and explain how they can reinforce each other.",evidence:"Use examples of successful integration of tradition and modernity.",link:"Connect to African identity and global participation."},vocab:["heritage","modernity","identity","tradition","innovation","culture","compatible","dichotomy"],sources:[{name:"UNESCO (2021)",fact:"Cultural and creative industries — drawing heavily on traditional knowledge, art, and craft — contribute over $50 billion annually to African economies and are growing at 5% per year."},{name:"McKinsey (2022)",fact:"The global Afrobeats music industry, rooted in African musical traditions, generated over $4.5 billion in revenue in 2022 and is projected to grow 15% annually."}],example:{point:"The supposed choice between cultural heritage and modernity is a false dichotomy: the most compelling examples of African success stories are precisely those that have achieved genuine integration of ancestral traditions with contemporary innovation.",explanation:"The assumption that African societies must choose between tradition and modernity reflects a particularly Western conception of historical progress. In reality, African traditions and modernity interact and enrich each other constantly. Afrobeats draws on generations of West African musical heritage while using the most sophisticated modern production technology. African fashion designers use traditional fabrics and techniques to create globally recognised contemporary designs.",evidence:"UNESCO (2021) reports that cultural industries drawing on traditional knowledge contribute $50 billion annually to African economies, while McKinsey (2022) notes the Afrobeats industry — rooted in tradition — generated $4.5 billion in 2022.",link:"The richer ambition for African societies is not to manage an impossible choice between heritage and modernity but to achieve the synthesis that creates something distinctively and powerfully African: rooted enough to be authentic, innovative enough to be relevant, and confident enough to engage the world on its own terms."}},
];
